#:pack{:created-at #inst "2026-05-04T05:44:16.825-00:00",
       :version "2026.05",
       :rules
       [#:rule{:title
               "API surface classes — internal (EDN/Transit), first-party cross-language (JSON/SSE/GraphQL), customer extension (REST/webhooks)",
               :agent-behavior
               "Every API in a miniforge product is one of three classes. The class\ndetermines the wire format, the contract stability expectations, and\nthe authentication / versioning posture. Mixing classes — or evolving\nan internal contract as if it were a public one — creates lock-in\nand customer-visible churn.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :audit,
                :message
                "Standard: API surface classes — internal (EDN/Transit), first-party cross-language (JSON/SSE/GraphQL), customer extension (REST/webhooks)"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:review :plan :implement},
                :file-globs
                ["**/*.clj"
                 "**/*.cljc"
                 "**/*.cljs"
                 "**/*.rs"
                 "**/*.py"
                 "**/*.ts"
                 "**/*.js"]},
               :severity :minor,
               :knowledge-content
               "# API surface classes\n\nEvery API in a miniforge product is one of three classes. The class\ndetermines the wire format, the contract stability expectations, and\nthe authentication / versioning posture. Mixing classes — or evolving\nan internal contract as if it were a public one — creates lock-in\nand customer-visible churn.\n\nThe architectural rule: **canonical domain model and external wire\nformats are not the same thing.** EDN is the semantic centre. Adapters\nproject EDN out to JSON, GraphQL, webhooks, exports.\n\n## The three classes\n\n| Class | Audience | Wire | Stability | Authentication |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **1. Internal domain boundary** | same product, same team, same language | EDN, Transit, EQL | refactor freely | trusted-process |\n| **2. First-party cross-language boundary** | own clients in other languages (native apps, Rust services, browser non-Fulcro consumers) | JSON-REST, SSE / WebSocket, possibly GraphQL | versioned, deprecation policy | session / OAuth / API key |\n| **3. Customer extension boundary** | third-party integrators, customer scripts, partner systems | REST/JSON, webhooks, signed callbacks, import / export formats, optional GraphQL | long-lived compatibility | API key / OAuth / signed requests |\n\n## API-001 — Choose the class explicitly\n\nEvery new API surface MUST declare its class in the namespace docstring\n(Clojure) or module-level comment (Rust/Python/etc.) and in the PR\ndescription. Implicit class assignment hides design decisions.\n\n```clojure\n(ns example.fleet-server.recommendations\n  \"API surface class 2 (first-party cross-language).\n   Wire: flat JSON over HTTP. Stable; versioned in the URL path.\n   Consumers: fleet-dashboard, native operator apps, customer SREs.\")\n```\n\n## API-002 — EDN is the canonical internal shape\n\nClass-1 surfaces use EDN (or Transit for over-the-wire CLJ↔CLJ) as\ntheir data shape. Domain events, internal commands and results, rule\nsources, fixtures, tests, and resolver inputs / outputs SHOULD be EDN.\n\nThis earns its keep when:\n\n- Clojure components compose without a JSON boundary in the middle\n- rules / policies compile to EDN data the runtime evaluates directly\n- fixtures and snapshots are diffable and human-readable\n- Fulcro / Pathom can consume the model without translation\n\n## API-003 — JSON for cross-language clients\n\nClass-2 surfaces MUST be JSON-flat, REST-shaped (or SSE / WebSocket for\nstreams). They MUST NOT require knowledge of EDN, EQL, Transit, or\nFulcro to consume.\n\n```\nGOOD:  GET /recommendations → {\"recommendations\": [{\"kind\":\"pause\", ...}]}\nBAD:   GET /recommendations → \"[#:recommendation{:kind :pause ...}]\"\n```\n\nThe internal model may be richer (namespaced keys, EDN sets) but the\nprojection at the class-2 boundary MUST translate to plain JSON\n(stringified keys, arrays for sets, ISO-8601 strings for instants).\n\nGraphQL is allowed at class 2 only when the client genuinely needs\nselective deep graph traversal that REST + a few endpoints can't\nexpress simply. Default to REST + SSE.\n\n## API-004 — Customer surfaces are intentionally narrow\n\nClass-3 surfaces MUST be:\n\n- documented separately from internal surfaces\n- versioned with a long-lived compatibility window (announced\n  deprecation periods, semver-style breaking-change policy)\n- minimal in surface area — every endpoint is a permanent commitment\n- delivered with reference SDKs or example code where possible\n\nWebhooks MUST be signed (HMAC or equivalent). Import / export formats\nMUST be text-based and stable (JSON, CSV, EDN) rather than internal\nbinary formats.\n\nClass-3 endpoints MUST NOT leak class-1 shapes (no Transit-encoded\nEDN, no `:namespaced/keywords` over the wire as keys).\n\n## API-005 — Do not promote without intent\n\nPromoting an internal (class-1) surface to a customer (class-3)\nsurface MUST be an explicit decision in an ADR. It is one-way: once a\ncustomer depends on a shape, you cannot quietly change it.\n\nA common failure mode: a private REST endpoint added \"just for the\ninternal dashboard\" gets discovered by a customer's script, becomes\nload-bearing, and traps the team into supporting an unintended\ncontract. Mitigate by:\n\n- documenting class-1 endpoints as internal in their docstring\n- requiring authenticated access for everything (no anonymous endpoints\n  except explicitly public ones like `/health`)\n- rate-limiting or path-prefixing internal endpoints (e.g. `/_internal/`)\n  so accidental adoption is visible and cheap to break\n\n## API-006 — Boundary patterns to recognise\n\nPatterns that recur across miniforge products. Use these to classify\nsurfaces in your own repo:\n\n- **OSS event envelope on the wire** (`{\"type\":\"event\",\"event_type\":...}`)\n  — class 2. Stable JSON-flat shape, intended for any consumer in any\n  language.\n- **Server REST** (`GET /<resource>`, `POST /<resource>/<id>/<action>`)\n  consumed by both first-party UIs and customer-side scripts — class 2.\n  Flat JSON, versioned, no namespaced keys on the wire.\n- **Fulcro internal Pathom / Transit surface** between a Fulcro UI and\n  its server — class 1. May use EQL, may use Transit, MUST NOT\n  replace the class-2 REST surface that other clients consume.\n- **In-process Clojure dependency** between two products in the same\n  workspace — class 1. Namespaces, protocols, EDN commands. No HTTP.\n- **Webhook / signed callback** delivered to customer-controlled\n  endpoints — class 3. Long-lived shape, signed payload, versioned.\n\n## Agent behaviour\n\nWhen designing or reviewing an API:\n1. State the class in the namespace docstring before writing handlers.\n2. If a class-2 endpoint emits a Transit-encoded blob, namespaced\n   keyword key, or EDN set, project it to JSON-flat shape.\n3. If a class-1 surface is being consumed by a class-2 client (e.g.\n   the native app reaches into a Pathom resolver directly), stop and\n   add a class-2 adapter.\n4. New customer-facing endpoints (class 3) require an ADR and a\n   versioning plan — no exceptions.",
               :id :std/api-surface-classes,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "332",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (332): API surface classes — internal (EDN/Transit), first-party cross-language (JSON/SSE/GraphQL), customer extension (REST/webhooks)"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Browser security — server-enforced authz, CSRF, no secrets in browser, blast-radius UI for destructive ops",
               :agent-behavior
               "Four invariants for any browser-facing surface in a miniforge product.\nThese are *blocker* severity — a violation MUST NOT merge.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :audit,
                :message
                "Standard: Browser security — server-enforced authz, CSRF, no secrets in browser, blast-radius UI for destructive ops"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:review :plan :implement},
                :file-globs
                ["**/*.html" "**/*.js" "**/*.cljs" "**/*.cljc"]},
               :severity :minor,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Browser security standards\n\nFour invariants for any browser-facing surface in a miniforge product.\nThese are *blocker* severity — a violation MUST NOT merge.\n\n## BSEC-001 — Server enforces authorization\n\nClient-side visibility MUST NOT be treated as authorization. Hiding a\nbutton does NOT prevent the underlying action; the server MUST refuse\nunauthorized requests independent of any UI gating.\n\n```\nBAD:  \"Only show the Delete Repo button to admins.\"\nGOOD: \"Only show the Delete Repo button to admins, AND have the server\n       refuse DELETE /repos/<id> from non-admin sessions.\"\n```\n\nIf the server-side check is missing, the UI gate is decorative and the\nendpoint is exploitable. Reject any PR adding privileged UI without the\nmatching server check.\n\n## BSEC-002 — CSRF protection required\n\nState-changing browser requests MUST include CSRF protection unless the\nauthentication mechanism makes CSRF structurally impossible (e.g.\nAuthorization header with a token NOT auto-attached by the browser).\n\nCookie-based sessions MUST use one of:\n- synchronizer token pattern (CSRF token in form / header, validated\n  server-side)\n- double-submit cookie pattern\n- `SameSite=Strict` or `SameSite=Lax` on the session cookie *plus* a\n  documented threat-model note\n\nGET requests MUST NOT change server state (this is also CSRF-relevant —\nforged GETs from `<img src>` don't carry CSRF tokens).\n\n## BSEC-003 — No secrets in browser code\n\nBrowser-shipped code (JS bundles, HTML, inline scripts, source maps)\nMUST NOT contain:\n\n- API secrets or service tokens\n- private keys (signing, encryption, JWT, etc.)\n- internal credentials of any kind\n- internal hostnames / IPs that aren't intended to be public\n- vendor API keys that aren't designed for browser exposure\n\nBrowser-safe identifiers (publishable Stripe keys, public OAuth client\nIDs, analytics property IDs) are fine but SHOULD be pulled from\nconfiguration, not hard-coded.\n\nIf a secret leaks in browser code, treat as a security incident: rotate\nthe secret first, then fix the code.\n\n## BSEC-004 — Destructive operations need blast-radius UI\n\nHigh-risk actions MUST show the affected resources before execution.\nThe user must see *what* they are about to break, not just *that* they\nare about to break something.\n\n| Action | Blast-radius preview |\n|---|---|\n| delete a repository integration | repos affected, workflows that depend on it |\n| revoke a credential | services that use it, last-used timestamp |\n| cancel running workflows | which runs, which agents, current step |\n| deactivate a policy pack | rules disabled, repos newly out of compliance |\n| change an environment | apps deployed there, current versions |\n\nPair this with JS-007 (typed confirmation for high blast radius) and\nFUL-023 (Fulcro mutations for destructive remote effects require prior\nUI confirmation).\n\n## Agent behaviour\n\nWhen writing or reviewing browser code:\n1. For every privileged UI gate, locate the matching server-side check.\n   No match → blocker.\n2. For every state-changing request, verify CSRF posture (header,\n   token, or SameSite documented).\n3. Grep the browser bundle for `key`, `secret`, `token`, `password`,\n   `credential` — investigate every hit.\n4. For every destructive action, confirm the UI shows blast-radius\n   *before* the confirmation prompt, not after.",
               :id :std/browser-security,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "331",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (331): Browser security — server-enforced authz, CSRF, no secrets in browser, blast-radius UI for destructive ops"}
        #:rule{:title "Clojure Polylith + per-file stratified design",
               :remediation
               {:strategy :mechanical,
                :replacement "(get $2 $1 $3)",
                :auto-fixable-default true,
                :exclude-contexts
                [{:path-contains "server/"}
                 {:current-contains
                  [":type" ":priority" ":status" ";; JSON"]}]},
               :agent-behavior
               "- **Exception**: Pure interface files (pass-throughs only) are not bound by the 3-layer maximum\n   - However, if an interface has >5 layers, consider if the component should be split into smaller components",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message
                "Standard: Clojure Polylith + per-file stratified design"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:review :implement},
                :file-globs
                ["components/**/src/**/*.clj"
                 "components/**/src/**/*.cljc"
                 "bases/**/src/**/*.clj"
                 "bases/**/src/**/*.cljc"
                 "projects/**/src/**/*.clj"
                 "projects/**/src/**/*.cljc"]},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Clojure style guidelines\n\n## Polylith architecture (ALWAYS)\n\n- Workspace: `components/`, `bases/`, `projects/`.\n\n- **Cross-component deps** must target `...<component>.interface` (not `.core`).\n- `bases` can depend on component **interfaces**; `projects` can depend on bases and component interfaces.\n- `components` may depend on other components **only via** their `.interface` ns.\n- **Never** depend on `projects` from `bases` or `components`.\n\n## Polylith stability tagging (ALWAYS)\n\n- Create stable tags **only after verification** (E2E tests + dogfooding runs), **not on every merge**.\n- Tag format: `git tag -a stable-YYYYMMDD -m \"Stable: <milestone description>\"`\n- Stable tags tell `poly info` which components have changed since last verified state.\n- Without stable tags, `poly info` shows all components as changed (since initial commit).\n- See **N1-architecture.md § 4.2.2** for complete tagging guidelines and verification checklist.\n\n## Per-file stratified design (ALWAYS)\n\n- Structure each ns with **labeled strata** as headings:\n\n  - `;------------------------------------------------------------------------------ Layer 0`\n  - `;------------------------------------------------------------------------------ Layer 1`\n  - …\n- **Reverse DAG**: Layer 0 at the top (pure/value-level); higher layers may call lower ones but not vice-versa.\n- **Max 3 strata** per file. If you need more, split the namespace.\n- Reserve the **very bottom** of the file for a `(comment …)` section (REPL testing). No `def/defn/defmacro` after it.\n\n## Component layout conventions\n\n### Required structure\n\n- `components/<name>/src/.../<name>/interface.clj` — **Complete public API surface**\n- `components/<name>/src/.../<name>/core.clj` — Main implementation (≤ 3 layers)\n- `components/<name>/src/.../<name>/spec.clj` — Malli schemas only; no functions except inside `(comment ...)`\n\n### Interface.clj pattern (CRITICAL)\n\n**Layer guidance for interfaces:**\n\n- The 3-layer maximum is **not a hard rule** for pure interface files that only contain pass-through functions\n- However, if an interface has many layers (>5), it may indicate the component is doing too much\n- Consider splitting large components into smaller, focused components to maintain simplicity and clear boundaries\n- Example: An agent component with 10 layers of pass-throughs might be better as separate planner,<br>\nimplementer, and tester components\n\n**Interface requirements:**\n\n- **interface.clj must contain ALL public functions** for the component\n- **interface.clj should contain NO implementations** — only thin pass-throughs\n- Pass-through functions forward to implementation functions in `core.clj` or other namespaces within the component\n- Input validation (specs) should happen in interface before forwarding\n- Example:\n\n  ```clojure\n  ;; CORRECT: interface.clj\n  (defn create-task\n    \"Create a new task (public API).\"\n    [task-data]\n    (s/validate ::task-spec task-data)\n    (core/create-task-impl task-data))\n\n  ;; WRONG: implementation in interface\n  (defn create-task [task-data]\n    (let [id (uuid/v4)\n          task (assoc task-data :id id)]\n      (store/save! task)))\n  ```\n\n### Implementation organization\n\n- **core.clj** — Main implementation logic; organized in ≤ 3 layers\n- **Additional namespaces** — When core.clj exceeds 3 layers or becomes too large:\n  - **Related functions** → subnamespaces (e.g., `views/table.clj`, `views/chart.clj`, `views/panel.clj`)\n  - **Unrelated functions** → separate namespaces (e.g., `executor.clj`, `factory.clj`, `validator.clj`)\n- **Protocol files** — `protocol.clj` for defining protocols/interfaces\n- All implementation namespaces are internal to the component; only `interface.clj` is public\n\n### Namespace splitting strategy\n\nWhen a file exceeds 3 layers:\n\n1. **Identify coherent groups** of functions\n2. **For related functions** (e.g., different views, different formatters):\n   - Create subnamespace: `components/<name>/src/.../<name>/<group>/<subname>.clj`\n   - Example: `reporting/views/table.clj`, `reporting/views/chart.clj`\n3. **For unrelated functions** (e.g., executor + factory + validator):\n   - Create separate namespaces: `components/<name>/src/.../<name>/<concern>.clj`\n   - Example: `agent/executor.clj`, `agent/factory.clj`, `agent/memory.clj`\n4. **Update interface.clj** to import and forward to new namespaces\n5. **Keep each new file** to ≤ 3 layers\n\n## Map access patterns (ALWAYS)\n\n- **Prefer `(get m k default)` over `(or (:k m) default)`**\n\n  ```clojure\n  ;; BAD — silently returns default for any falsy value (false, 0, \"\")\n  (or (:timeout opts) 5000)\n\n  ;; GOOD — explicit default, survives falsy values\n  (get opts :timeout 5000)\n  ```\n\n- The `(or (:k m) fallback)` form is only acceptable when choosing between two\n  **different keys** in the same map (canonical vs. legacy field), never when\n  `fallback` is a computed or literal default:\n\n  ```clojure\n  ;; Acceptable — picking between two key names for the same semantic field\n  (or (get event :workflow/id) (get event :workflow-id))\n\n  ;; BAD — use get with default instead\n  (or (:workflow/id event) \"unknown\")          ; → (get event :workflow/id \"unknown\")\n  (or (:tokens result) total-tokens)           ; → (get result :tokens total-tokens)\n  ```\n\n## Anonymous functions (ALWAYS)\n\nAnonymous functions (`fn` / `#(...)`) should be used **only when they enhance\nthe clarity of the surrounding code** — not as a default for every callback.\n\n**Prefer named functions when:**\n\n- The logic has a name worth expressing (extract to `defn-`)\n- The body is more than one non-trivial expression\n- The function is used more than once\n- The parent expression already reads at a high level of abstraction and the\n  anonymous body forces the reader to shift mental levels mid-expression\n\n**Acceptable anonymous function uses:**\n\n```clojure\n;; Short, self-evident predicate inline — intent is clear from context\n(filter :active? users)\n(remove nil? results)\n(keep :name items)\n\n;; Simple structural transform that names itself through context\n(map #(assoc % :processed? true) records)\n\n;; One-off adaptor that has no reusable name\n(sort-by #(get key->cat %) rule-ids)\n```\n\n**Extract to a named function when the body obscures intent:**\n\n```clojure\n;; BAD — the anon fn body is complex and the parent reads poorly\n(into {} (map (fn [[k vs]]\n                [k (get (first vs) :rule/category \"0\")])\n              groups))\n\n;; GOOD — named fn expresses the intent; parent reads as a pipeline\n(defn- key->category-entry [[k vs]]\n  [k (get (first vs) :rule/category \"0\")])\n\n(into {} (map key->category-entry groups))\n```\n\n**Never embed anonymous functions in data maps as configuration values.**\nConfiguration maps should reference named functions so the config remains\ndata and the behavior is separately testable:\n\n```clojure\n;; BAD — anonymous fn buried in a map; untestable, hard to read\n{:file-pred (fn [path] (str/ends-with? path \".clj\"))}\n\n;; GOOD — named fn at the correct stratum; referenced by the config\n(defn- clojure-file? [path] (str/ends-with? path \".clj\"))\n\n{:file-pred clojure-file?}\n```\n\n## Agent behavior\n\nWhen creating/editing a namespace:\n\n1) Insert/maintain **Layer 0/1/2** headings and keep them **monotonic increasing** (0 → 1 → 2).\n2) Keep **pure helpers** and external calls that are side-effect free in **Layer 0**.\n3) Put orchestration that **only depends on Layer 0** in **Layer 1**, and so on.\n4) If you cross 3 layers, **propose a split** using the namespace splitting strategy above.\n   - **Exception**: Pure interface files (pass-throughs only) are not bound by the 3-layer maximum\n   - However, if an interface has >5 layers, consider if the component should be split into smaller components\n5) Ensure the last top-level form is a single `(comment …)` block with quick REPL samples.\n6) For cross-component calls, target `...<other>.interface` — and surface a fix if `.core` is used.\n\n## Examples\n\n### Good: Thin interface with pass-through\n\n```clojure\n;; components/task/src/ai/miniforge/task/interface.clj\n(ns ai.miniforge.task.interface\n  (:require [ai.miniforge.task.core :as core]\n            [ai.miniforge.task.validator :as validator]))\n\n;------------------------------------------------------------------------------ Layer 0\n;; Public API - validation + forwarding only\n\n(defn create-task\n  \"Create a new task.\"\n  [task-data]\n  (validator/validate-task-data task-data)\n  (core/create-task-impl task-data))\n\n(defn get-task\n  \"Retrieve task by ID.\"\n  [task-id]\n  (core/get-task-impl task-id))\n```\n\n### Good: Split oversized file by related functions\n\n```clojure\n;; Before: reporting/views.clj with 8 layers\n;; After:\n;; - reporting/views/table.clj (≤3 layers)\n;; - reporting/views/chart.clj (≤3 layers)\n;; - reporting/views/panel.clj (≤3 layers)\n\n;; components/reporting/src/ai/miniforge/reporting/interface.clj\n(ns ai.miniforge.reporting.interface\n  (:require [ai.miniforge.reporting.views.table :as table]\n            [ai.miniforge.reporting.views.chart :as chart]\n            [ai.miniforge.reporting.views.panel :as panel]))\n\n(defn render-table [data] (table/render data))\n(defn render-chart [data] (chart/render data))\n(defn render-panel [data] (panel/render data))\n```\n\n### Bad: Implementation in interface\n\n```clojure\n;; components/task/src/ai/miniforge/task/interface.clj\n(ns ai.miniforge.task.interface\n  (:require [datalevin.core :as d]))\n\n;; WRONG: Implementation details in interface\n(defn create-task [task-data]\n  (let [conn (d/get-conn)\n        id (java.util.UUID/randomUUID)\n        task (assoc task-data :id id :created-at (java.time.Instant/now))]\n    (d/transact! conn [task])\n    task))\n```",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/clojure,
               :detection
               {:type :content-scan,
                :pattern
                "\\(or \\((:[a-zA-Z][a-zA-Z0-9?!_*+<>-]*)\\s+([a-zA-Z][a-zA-Z0-9_-]*)\\)\\s+((?:nil|true|false|\"[^\"]*\"|-?\\d+(?:\\.\\d+)?|\\[\\]|\\{\\}|:[a-zA-Z][a-zA-Z0-9_-]*))\\)",
                :mode :positive},
               :category "210",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (210): Clojure Polylith + per-file stratified design"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Clojure exception handling — prefer slingshot `try+` / `throw+`; plain `try` only in narrow exemptions (no-slingshot-dep leaf catch, leaf inside `try+`, REPL/`(comment …)`)",
               :agent-behavior
               "- Default new catch sites to `try+`; add the slingshot require if absent.\n- If the throw site is `throw+` / `throw-anomaly!`, the catch site MUST be `try+` — never plain `try` digging into `ex-data` for `:anomaly/category`.\n- Reject `try+` whose every catch is class-only AND the component has no other slingshot use — either commit to `try+` across the component or drop the `+`.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message
                "Standard: Clojure exception handling — prefer slingshot `try+` / `throw+`; plain `try` only in narrow exemptions (no-slingshot-dep leaf catch, leaf inside `try+`, REPL/`(comment …)`)"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:review :implement},
                :file-globs
                ["components/**/src/**/*.clj"
                 "components/**/src/**/*.cljc"
                 "bases/**/src/**/*.clj"
                 "bases/**/src/**/*.cljc"
                 "projects/**/src/**/*.clj"
                 "projects/**/src/**/*.cljc"]},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Clojure exception handling — prefer `try+` / `throw+`\n\nSlingshot's `try+` is a **strict superset** of Clojure's `try`. It catches\nevery Throwable that `try` does (selector form: class name → `(instance?\n<class-name> %)`), and adds three more selector forms — key-value vectors,\npredicates, and `%`-substituting selector forms — that operate on the\nthrown value's shape.\n\nThere is no functional reason to choose `try` over `try+` once slingshot\nis on the component's classpath. New code defaults to `try+`. Legacy `try`\nsites are not a defect on their own and don't need urgent rewrites, but\nshould converge on `try+` opportunistically and during the post-dogfood\naudit (see `project/dogfood-readiness` follow-up notes).\n\nThis rule is the operational complement to:\n\n- `foundations/result-handling` (003) — return anomalies as data; predicates\n  / constructors over hand-built maps.\n- `foundations/exceptions-as-data` (005) — throws are reserved for absolute\n  process boundaries; flows return anomalies.\n\nWhen you DO catch — at one of those boundaries — this rule says *which form*.\n\n## Default: `try+`\n\nFor any component that already imports slingshot (or that catches anything\nbeyond a single trivial Java class), use `try+`:\n\n```clojure\n(:require [slingshot.slingshot :refer [try+ throw+]])\n\n;; Catches everything plain `try` catches (class selector)…\n(try+\n  (.read input)\n  (catch IOException _ nil))\n\n;; …and dispatches on the thrown map's shape (key-value selector)…\n(try+\n  (verify-budget! state)\n  (catch [:anomaly/category :anomalies.budget/exceeded] anomaly\n    (escalate! anomaly)))\n\n;; …and on a predicate, or a `%`-substituting form, or a destructured map.\n(try+\n  (do-thing)\n  (catch map? m (handle-map m))\n  (catch #(= :recoverable (:severity %))\n         {:keys [reason]}\n    (recover! reason)))\n```\n\n`&throw-context` inside any catch clause carries `:object`, `:message`,\n`:cause`, `:stack-trace`, and (for non-Throwable catches) `:wrapper` and\n`:throwable`. That introspection is available even when the only selector\nin the form is a Java class.\n\n## Allowed: plain `try`\n\n`try` is acceptable in three narrow cases:\n\n1. **The component has no slingshot dep and adding one would only be for\n   this catch.** Adding `slingshot/slingshot` is small but real footprint;\n   if the component otherwise has no use for it, plain `try` keeps the\n   dep graph tight.\n\n2. **A leaf `try` inside a `try+` body** that exists only to satisfy a\n   Java try-with-resources / try-finally pattern that's clearer with\n   class-only catches. Slingshot supports nested forms; readability wins.\n\n3. **REPL / scratch / `(comment …)` blocks** where the import overhead\n   isn't worth it.\n\nIn any of these cases, the choice is **deliberate**, named in a code\ncomment if non-obvious, and reviewable.\n\n## When you DO throw\n\nThrowing is reserved for absolute boundaries (per `foundations/exceptions-\nas-data`). When you throw at a boundary:\n\n- **Use `throw+` (or `response.anomaly/throw-anomaly!`) for structured\n  payloads.** A map carries the anomaly category, the offending values,\n  any actionable context. `try+` consumers can dispatch on\n  `:anomaly/category` directly — no `ex-data` digging.\n\n```clojure\n(throw-anomaly! :anomalies.llm/rate-limited\n                \"Rate limit hit\"\n                {:anomaly.llm/backend :anthropic :status 429})\n```\n\n- **Use plain `throw` only for genuine Java/JVM exceptions** that you want\n  to propagate as a Throwable (e.g., `IllegalArgumentException` for an\n  exhaustive case match — see `foundations/exceptions-as-data` §\n  programmer-error guards).\n\n## Anti-patterns to reject\n\n- **`try+` block with one class-only catch when the component has no other\n  slingshot use** — adds a dep without reason. Either drop the `+` or\n  introduce `try+` consistently across the component's catch sites.\n\n- **Plain `try` catching a value thrown by `throw+` / `throw-anomaly!`.**\n  The catch site reaches into `ex-data` to read the anomaly's category,\n  defeating the structured contract. Use `try+` and a key-value selector.\n\n  ```clojure\n  ;; BAD — plain try, ex-data digging, brittle\n  (try\n    (verify-budget! state)\n    (catch Exception e\n      (when (= :anomalies.budget/exceeded\n               (-> e ex-data :anomaly/category))\n        (escalate!))))\n\n  ;; GOOD — try+, key-value selector reads the anomaly directly\n  (try+\n    (verify-budget! state)\n    (catch [:anomaly/category :anomalies.budget/exceeded] _\n      (escalate!)))\n  ```\n\n- **Switching between `try` and `try+` mid-component for stylistic\n  consistency only.** If the component's catch sites all see Java classes\n  today and it has no slingshot dep, leaving them as `try` is fine.\n  Mass-rewriting them just to \"match\" a new `try+` site dilutes diff\n  signal without behavior change.\n\n- **Using `throw` to throw a map (no `ex-info`) and catching with `try`.**\n  This works (the wrapper handling is implicit) but loses every readability\n  benefit of slingshot. Use `throw+` and `try+`.\n\n## Migration posture\n\nThe miniforge codebase as of 2026-05-04 has ~7 `try+` callsites and ~240\nplain `try` callsites. The plain-`try` count is not a bug list — most of\nthose sites catch a single Java class, swallow the failure, and would\ngain nothing from the value-shape selectors. They predate this rule.\n\nWhen picking up legacy code:\n\n1. If you're already editing a callsite for unrelated reasons and the\n   component already imports slingshot, switch the form to `try+` —\n   essentially free.\n2. If the component does not yet import slingshot and the catch is\n   class-only, leave `try` alone unless something else in the same PR\n   pulls slingshot in.\n3. Don't open standalone \"convert try to try+\" PRs while dogfood\n   stabilization is in progress — the migration audit is scheduled for\n   the consistently-passing phase, prepping for the next major release\n   (see `project_try_plus_migration` memory).\n\n## Agent behavior\n\n- Default new catch sites to `try+`; add the slingshot require if absent.\n- If the throw site is `throw+` / `throw-anomaly!`, the catch site MUST be `try+` — never plain `try` digging into `ex-data` for `:anomaly/category`.\n- Reject `try+` whose every catch is class-only AND the component has no other slingshot use — either commit to `try+` across the component or drop the `+`.\n- Plain `try` is allowed only in three narrow cases: (a) component has no slingshot dep and adding one would be solely for this catch; (b) leaf `try` nested inside a `try+` body for try-finally clarity; (c) REPL / `(comment …)` blocks.\n- Don't mass-migrate. Convergence is opportunistic during normal work; full audit deferred to post-dogfood readiness.\n\n## Examples\n\n<example>\nMixed selectors in one form — slingshot's actual strength.\n\n```clojure\n(try+\n  (run-step ctx)\n  (catch [:anomaly/category :anomalies.llm/rate-limited]\n         {:keys [anomaly.llm/backend]}\n    (backoff! backend))\n  (catch IOException _e\n    (response/failure :step/io-failed))\n  (catch map? anomaly\n    (response/failure anomaly)))\n```\n</example>\n\n<example>\nPlain `try` is fine here — leaf component with one class-only catch and\nno other slingshot use.\n\n```clojure\n(ns ai.miniforge.tiny-util.core)\n\n(defn parse-int-safe [s]\n  (try\n    (Long/parseLong s)\n    (catch NumberFormatException _ nil)))\n```\n</example>\n\n<example type=\"invalid\">\nPlain `try` digging into `ex-data` to read an anomaly the producer threw\nvia `throw+`. Replace with `try+` and a key-value selector.\n\n```clojure\n(try\n  (verify-budget! state)\n  (catch Exception e\n    (when (= :anomalies.budget/exceeded\n             (-> e ex-data :anomaly/category))\n      (escalate!))))\n```\n</example>\n\n<example type=\"invalid\">\n`try+` with a single class-only catch in a component with no other\nslingshot use. Either drop the `+` or commit to `try+` across the\ncomponent's catch sites.\n\n```clojure\n(ns ai.miniforge.tiny-util.core\n  (:require [slingshot.slingshot :refer [try+]]))\n\n(try+\n  (.read input)\n  (catch IOException _ nil))\n```\n</example>",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/clojure-exception-handling,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "211",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (211): Clojure exception handling — prefer slingshot `try+` / `throw+`; plain `try` only in narrow exemptions (no-slingshot-dep leaf catch, leaf inside `try+`, REPL/`(comment …)`)"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Code quality — composable pipelines, no nested conditionals, DRY component extraction",
               :agent-behavior
               "When writing or reviewing code:\n1. If a function exceeds one screen, ask: can this be split into named pipeline stages?\n2. If you see nested `if`/`when` blocks, refactor to `cond` or guard clauses.\n3. If you find yourself duplicating a function from another namespace, stop — create or identify the right component and add it to the interface.\n4. Composition is the design. Don't name composed pipelines \"main\" or \"run\" — name them for what they produce.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message
                "Standard: Code quality — composable pipelines, no nested conditionals, DRY component extraction"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement}},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Code Quality (ALWAYS)\n\n## Composable functions — small and pipeline-oriented\n\nEvery function must read as a **pipeline**: data enters, transforms, exits. No hidden branches, no side effects buried in the middle, no implicit state mutations.\n\n**Design rule:** Write the smallest function that does one thing. Compose up.\n\n```clojure\n;; BAD — one function does discovery, filtering, and formatting\n(defn process-results [items]\n  (let [results []]\n    (doseq [item items]\n      (when (valid? item)\n        (when-let [x (transform item)]\n          (conj results (format x)))))\n    results))\n\n;; GOOD — three pure functions, each one concern\n(defn valid-items   [items]   (filter valid? items))\n(defn transform-all [items]   (keep transform items))\n(defn format-all    [items]   (mapv format items))\n\n;; Composed pipeline — reads as data flow\n(defn process-results [items]\n  (-> items valid-items transform-all format-all))\n```\n\nThe composed form is **the function** — not a \"main\" that calls helpers. There is no incidental complexity.\n\n## No nested conditionals\n\nNested `if`/`cond`/`when` blocks are a signal that control flow and data transformation are entangled. Restructure instead.\n\n**Prefer:**\n- Guard clauses (`when`/`if` at the top, return early via `nil` or exception)\n- `cond->` / `cond->>` for conditional transformation chains\n- Lookup tables / dispatch maps over `cond` branches\n- `some->` / `some->>` for optional-chain patterns\n\n```clojure\n;; BAD — nested conditionals\n(defn classify [evt]\n  (if (= :workflow/started (:event/type evt))\n    (if-let [id (:workflow/id evt)]\n      (if (valid-id? id)\n        :valid-start\n        :bad-id)\n      :missing-id)\n    :not-a-start))\n\n;; GOOD — flat cond\n(defn classify [evt]\n  (let [type (:event/type evt)\n        id   (:workflow/id evt)]\n    (cond\n      (not= :workflow/started type) :not-a-start\n      (nil? id)                     :missing-id\n      (not (valid-id? id))          :bad-id\n      :else                         :valid-start)))\n```\n\nA maximum of **one level of conditional nesting** is the goal. Two levels demands a refactor. Three is never acceptable.\n\n## DRY — extract to a component, import the interface\n\nDuplication of logic is a signal that a component boundary is missing.\n\n**Rules:**\n- If two components share more than one helper function, that logic belongs in a third component.\n- Never copy-paste implementations across namespaces. If you find yourself doing so, stop and create a shared component.\n- The shared component exposes an `interface.clj`. Consumers depend on the interface, never on the internal namespace.\n\n```\n;; BAD: same timestamp normalization in events.clj and workflows.clj\n(defn normalize-ts [ts] ...)  ; duplicated!\n\n;; GOOD: shared component\ncomponents/temporal/src/ai/miniforge/temporal/interface.clj\n  (def normalize-ts core/normalize-ts)\n\n;; Consumers:\n(:require [ai.miniforge.temporal.interface :as temporal])\n(temporal/normalize-ts ts)\n```\n\n**What belongs in a component:**\n- Any pure function used in more than one component\n- Any protocol/schema referenced across components\n- Any formatting or parsing utility with multiple callers\n\n**What stays local:**\n- Functions called only within one component's internal namespaces\n\n## Agent behavior\n\nWhen writing or reviewing code:\n1. If a function exceeds one screen, ask: can this be split into named pipeline stages?\n2. If you see nested `if`/`when` blocks, refactor to `cond` or guard clauses.\n3. If you find yourself duplicating a function from another namespace, stop — create or identify the right component and add it to the interface.\n4. Composition is the design. Don't name composed pipelines \"main\" or \"run\" — name them for what they produce.\n\n## Anti-patterns to reject\n\n- Functions with multiple concerns named after a verb (e.g., `process-and-save`, `load-and-validate`)\n- `let` bindings that grow to 10+ forms — split the function\n- `cond` branches with `let` bodies — extract each branch to a named function\n- Utility functions copied between components instead of extracted\n- \"Helper\" files that grow without bound because no component owns them",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/code-quality,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "002",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (002): Code quality — composable pipelines, no nested conditionals, DRY component extraction"}
        #:rule{:title
               "CSS — design tokens, semantic class names, shallow selectors, accessible focus",
               :agent-behavior
               "CSS in any miniforge web surface SHOULD lean on design tokens,\ncomponent-purpose class names, and shallow selectors. No hard-coded\nproduct colours; no anti-accessible focus suppression.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :audit,
                :message
                "Standard: CSS — design tokens, semantic class names, shallow selectors, accessible focus"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:review :implement},
                :file-globs ["**/*.css" "**/*.scss"]},
               :severity :minor,
               :knowledge-content
               "# CSS standards\n\nCSS in any miniforge web surface SHOULD lean on design tokens,\ncomponent-purpose class names, and shallow selectors. No hard-coded\nproduct colours; no anti-accessible focus suppression.\n\n## CSS-001 — Use design tokens\n\nCSS MUST use shared custom properties for product colours, spacing,\ntypography, borders, shadows, and radii. Tokens live at `:root` (or a\nshared `tokens.css`) and are referenced via `var(--token-name)`.\n\n```css\n:root {\n  --color-bg: #0f172a;\n  --color-surface: #1e293b;\n  --color-accent: #14b8a6;\n  --color-accent-soft: #a7f3d0;\n  --space-1: 0.25rem;\n  --space-2: 0.5rem;\n  --space-4: 1rem;\n  --radius-md: 0.5rem;\n}\n```\n\n## CSS-002 — No hardcoded product colours outside tokens\n\n```css\n/* BAD */\n.button { background: #14b8a6; }\n\n/* GOOD */\n.button { background: var(--color-accent); }\n```\n\nThe only acceptable hex/RGB literals in CSS are inside the token\ndefinitions themselves. Anywhere else is a violation.\n\n## CSS-003 — Name classes by component purpose\n\n| Acceptable | Not acceptable |\n|---|---|\n| `.policy-card` | `.big-blue-box` |\n| `.workflow-run-list` | `.left-thing` |\n| `.evidence-panel` | `.new-style` |\n| `.repo-status-badge` | `.thing-2` |\n\nVisual-only names (`.red`, `.large`, `.bold`) are forbidden. They tie\nmarkup to current visual style and break the moment the design changes.\n\n## CSS-004 — Avoid deep selector chains\n\nSelectors SHOULD NOT exceed three levels.\n\n```css\n/* BAD */\n.main .content .panel .body .row button span {}\n\n/* GOOD */\n.policy-card__action {}\n```\n\nDeep chains are a smell that the markup needs better named hooks (see\nCSS-003) or that the rule is over-coupled to DOM structure.\n\n## CSS-005 — Use reusable layout utilities\n\nCommon layout patterns SHOULD be expressed as named utilities, not\nre-coded per component.\n\nRecommended utilities to factor out:\n\n- `.stack` — vertical rhythm with consistent gap\n- `.cluster` — horizontal flex with wrap and gap\n- `.grid` — CSS grid with sensible defaults\n- `.sidebar-layout` — main/aside split that collapses responsively\n- `.page-shell` — top-level page chrome\n\n## CSS-006 — Responsive layout required\n\nNew pages MUST be usable at:\n\n- 390px width (mobile) unless explicitly desktop-only\n- 1280px (laptop)\n- large desktop monitor widths (1920px+)\n\nDocument any \"desktop-only\" exception in the page's PR description.\n\n## CSS-007 — Visible focus states required\n\nInteractive elements MUST define a visible `:focus-visible` style.\n\n```css\n.button:focus-visible {\n  outline: 2px solid var(--color-accent);\n  outline-offset: 2px;\n}\n```\n\n## CSS-008 — Do not hide focus without replacement\n\n```css\n/* BAD — hides focus globally with no replacement */\n*:focus { outline: none; }\n```\n\nFocus suppression is allowed only when paired with an equivalent visible\nfocus indicator on the same selector. Reject any rule that removes\nfocus styling without compensation.\n\n## Agent behaviour\n\nWhen writing or reviewing CSS:\n1. Grep for hex/RGB/HSL literals outside the tokens file — each is a\n   CSS-002 violation.\n2. Count selector depth on any new rule; >3 levels gets refactored.\n3. Verify every interactive element class has a `:focus-visible` partner.\n4. Check for `outline: 0`, `outline: none`, `:focus { outline:` —\n   reject unless replaced.",
               :id :std/css,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "260",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (260): CSS — design tokens, semantic class names, shallow selectors, accessible focus"}
        #:rule{:title "DateVer versioning convention",
               :remediation
               {:strategy :mechanical,
                :replacement "$1.$2.$3.0",
                :auto-fixable-default false},
               :agent-behavior
               "- When generating versions, use `(version)` from build.clj\n- Never use SemVer (X.Y.Z) format\n- In changelogs, use DateVer headings: `## 2026.01.18.1`",
               :enforcement
               {:action :audit,
                :message "Standard: DateVer versioning convention"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement},
                :file-globs
                ["build.clj"
                 "**/version.edn"
                 ".github/workflows/*.yml"
                 ".github/workflows/*.yaml"]},
               :severity :minor,
               :knowledge-content
               "# DateVer Versioning (ALWAYS)\n\nUse **DateVer** instead of SemVer for all version numbers.\n\n## Format\n\n```zsh\nYYYY.MM.DD.N\n```\n\nWhere:\n\n- `YYYY` — four-digit year\n- `MM` — two-digit month (zero-padded)\n- `DD` — two-digit day (zero-padded)\n- `N` — build number for the day (1-indexed)\n\n## Examples\n\n| Version | Meaning |\n|---------|---------|\n| `2026.01.18.1` | First build on January 18, 2026 |\n| `2026.01.18.5` | Fifth build on January 18, 2026 |\n| `2026.03.01.1` | First build on March 1, 2026 |\n\n## Rationale\n\n- **Chronologically sortable**: Versions naturally sort by time\n- **No arbitrary major/minor**: Avoids bikeshedding about \"breaking changes\"\n- **Self-documenting**: Version tells you when it was built\n- **Simple**: One rule—today's date plus build count\n\n## Implementation\n\n```clojure\n;; In build.clj\n(defn version []\n  (let [now   (java.time.LocalDate/now)\n        year  (.getYear now)\n        month (.getMonthValue now)\n        day   (.getDayOfMonth now)\n        n     (today-commit-count)]\n    (format \"%d.%02d.%02d.%d\" year month day n)))\n```\n\n## Git Tags\n\nTag releases as `v{version}`:\n\n```bash\ngit tag v2026.01.18.1\ngit push origin v2026.01.18.1\n```\n\n## Comparison to SemVer\n\n| SemVer | DateVer | Notes |\n|--------|---------|-------|\n| 1.0.0 | 2026.01.15.1 | Initial release |\n| 1.0.1 | 2026.01.15.2 | Bug fix same day |\n| 1.1.0 | 2026.01.20.1 | Feature add |\n| 2.0.0 | 2026.03.01.1 | \"Breaking change\" (no special handling) |\n\nBreaking changes are communicated via changelog and documentation, not version numbers.\n\n## Agent Behavior\n\n- When generating versions, use `(version)` from build.clj\n- Never use SemVer (X.Y.Z) format\n- In changelogs, use DateVer headings: `## 2026.01.18.1`",
               :id :std/datever,
               :detection
               {:type :content-scan,
                :pattern "\\b(\\d+)\\.(\\d+)\\.(\\d+)\\b(?!\\.\\d)",
                :mode :positive},
               :category "730",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (730): DateVer versioning convention"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Exceptions are data — return anomalies in normal flows; throw only at absolute boundaries",
               :agent-behavior
               "1. **Default to anomaly returns.** If a function in a non-boundary namespace can fail, return an anomaly map.\n2. **Reach for `(anomaly/anomaly type message data)`**, not `(throw (ex-info ...))`.\n3. **At boundaries, use `boundary/execute-with-exception-handling`** (or the local equivalent) to wrap calls into libraries that throw. Convert their exceptions into anomaly steps.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message
                "Standard: Exceptions are data — return anomalies in normal flows; throw only at absolute boundaries"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement}},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Exceptions Are Data, Not Control Flow (ALWAYS)\n\nOperations that can fail return an **anomaly** as data, not a thrown exception. Exceptions are caught only at absolute process boundaries (HTTP/CLI/MCP/message-consumer entry points) and *converted* into anomaly-shaped data that participates in the composable flow.\n\nCompanion rule to result-handling (003) and validation-boundaries (004). Result-handling defines the result-map shape and predicates. Validation-boundaries defines *where* validation occurs. This rule defines *how errors propagate* — as data, not stack-unwinding.\n\n## The rule\n\nIn a non-boundary namespace, `throw` is a code smell. Two narrow exemptions:\n\n1. **Absolute process boundaries** — see \"Boundary namespace patterns\" below.\n2. **Programmer-error guards** — `IllegalArgumentException` for an exhaustive case match, assertions on impossible-by-construction conditions inside pure helpers.\n\nEverywhere else: return an anomaly.\n\n## Why\n\nComposable AI/agent pipelines need to carry error context alongside successful output. Three problems with exceptions as the default failure path:\n\n- **They lose data.** The stack unwinds past the structured information you wanted to return. Whatever the failing function knew about the failure is gone unless it stuffs it into `ex-info` data, and even then it travels via a side channel rather than the normal return path.\n- **They break parallel composition.** A throw in one branch of a parallel fan-out poisons the whole computation. Anomalies returned as data let the orchestrator inspect each result.\n- **They don't carry provenance.** A response-chain accumulates per-operation anomalies in order, with each step's `:operation` keyword. A thrown exception gives you a stack trace and nothing about what came before it.\n\nData-first errors fold into the same response-chain / evidence-bundle machinery that carries success. That is the difference between \"a RAG toy\" and \"a consumer product that can answer 'why?'.\"\n\n## Anomaly shape\n\nThe canonical anomaly map. The shared implementation is the `ai.miniforge.anomaly` component in miniforge OSS (Apache 2); when miniforge is unavailable, repos may use a local helper that produces the same shape.\n\n```clojure\n{:anomaly/type    :keyword     ;; one of the standard types below\n :anomaly/message \"string\"     ;; human-readable\n :anomaly/data    {...}        ;; structured context\n :anomaly/at      #inst \"...\"} ;; instant of construction\n```\n\nStandard type vocabulary (mirrors cognitect anomalies):\n\n```clojure\n#{:not-found\n  :invalid-input\n  :unauthorized\n  :fault\n  :unavailable\n  :conflict\n  :timeout\n  :unsupported\n  :fatal}\n```\n\nConstruct via `(anomaly/anomaly type message data)`. Test via `(anomaly/anomaly? x)`. Validate via the exported `Anomaly` malli schema.\n\n## Boundary namespace patterns\n\n`throw` and `ex-info` are appropriate in these namespace shapes:\n\n| Pattern | Examples | Why |\n|---------|----------|-----|\n| `*.cli.*` / `*-main` | `bases/cli/...`, `*-main` namespaces | Top-level CLI entry; throw produces a clean exit status |\n| `*.boundary.*` | `ai.miniforge.boundary.*` | Designated exception → anomaly converter component |\n| `*.http.*` / `*.web.*` | HTTP request handlers | The HTTP machinery expects exceptions to render error responses |\n| `*.mcp.*` | MCP tool entry | MCP protocol surfaces errors as throws |\n| `*.consumer.*` / `*.listener.*` | Message-consumer entry points | The consumer framework converts throws to retries / DLQ |\n| Fns named `execute-with-exception-handling` (or similar) | Anywhere | Designated catch-and-convert helpers |\n\nAnything *outside* those patterns should return anomalies.\n\n## Examples\n\n### Violation — throwing inside non-boundary code\n\n```clojure\n;; BAD — components/widget/src/ai/miniforge/widget/core.clj\n(defn fetch-widget\n  [store id]\n  (or (get-widget store id)\n      (throw (ex-info \"Widget not found\" {:id id}))))\n```\n\nThree problems: caller has to wrap every call in try/catch; the anomaly's `:type` and `:data` are buried in `ex-data`; parallel `(map fetch-widget …)` fan-outs break on the first miss.\n\n### Correction — return an anomaly\n\n```clojure\n;; GOOD — components/widget/src/ai/miniforge/widget/core.clj\n(ns ai.miniforge.widget.core\n  (:require [ai.miniforge.anomaly.interface :as anomaly]))\n\n(defn fetch-widget\n  [store id]\n  (if-let [w (get-widget store id)]\n    w\n    (anomaly/anomaly :not-found\n                     \"Widget not found\"\n                     {:id id})))\n```\n\nCaller inspects with `anomaly/anomaly?`; parallel calls collect both successes and failures cleanly.\n\n### Acceptable — boundary catches and converts\n\n```clojure\n;; GOOD — bases/cli/src/ai/miniforge/cli/main.clj\n(ns ai.miniforge.cli.main\n  (:require [ai.miniforge.boundary.interface :as boundary]\n            [ai.miniforge.widget.interface :as widget]))\n\n(defn -main\n  [& args]\n  (let [chain (boundary/execute-with-exception-handling\n                :widget-fetch\n                (response-chain/create-chain :widget-cli)\n                :widget/fetch\n                widget/fetch-widget store id)]\n    (if (response-chain/succeeded? chain)\n      (System/exit 0)\n      (do (print-anomaly (response-chain/last-anomaly chain))\n          (System/exit 1)))))\n```\n\nBoundary helper catches throws (from underlying libraries that *do* throw), converts to anomaly steps in the chain, returns the chain as data.\n\n### Acceptable — programmer-error guard\n\n```clojure\n;; GOOD — exhaustive case match on an enum-like value\n(case kind\n  :collection ...\n  :conversation ...\n  :event ...\n  ;; default: unknown kind is a programmer error, not a runtime error\n  (throw (IllegalArgumentException.\n          (str \"Unknown kind: \" kind))))\n```\n\nThis isn't a runtime failure to be recovered from — it's \"I added a new variant and forgot to handle it here.\" Throw is appropriate.\n\n## Agent behavior\n\nWhen writing or reviewing component code:\n\n1. **Default to anomaly returns.** If a function in a non-boundary namespace can fail, return an anomaly map.\n2. **Reach for `(anomaly/anomaly type message data)`**, not `(throw (ex-info ...))`.\n3. **At boundaries, use `boundary/execute-with-exception-handling`** (or the local equivalent) to wrap calls into libraries that throw. Convert their exceptions into anomaly steps.\n4. **When reviewing PRs**, flag any `throw` or `ex-info` in non-boundary code paths. Suggest the anomaly-return rewrite. Programmer-error guards (exhaustive case matches, impossible-by-construction assertions) get a pass.\n5. **Don't rewrite library code that throws.** That's outside our control. Catch at the boundary.\n\n## Anti-patterns to reject\n\n- `(throw (ex-info \"...\" {...}))` inside `core.clj` of a Polylith component\n- `try/catch` blocks inside non-boundary code paths used to convert thrown exceptions into return values — instead, fix the called function to return an anomaly directly\n- Mixed signaling: a function that *sometimes* returns `nil`, *sometimes* returns an anomaly, *sometimes* throws — pick one (anomaly)\n- \"Throwing for control flow\" — using `throw`/`try` to exit a deep loop or short-circuit a computation. Use proper return paths.\n- Catching `Throwable` deep inside business logic — only boundary helpers should catch, and they catch deliberately\n\n## Linter design\n\nThis rule prescribes the linter shape; the implementation will land in miniforge OSS `bb review` once the canonical anomaly component is in place. The design:\n\nScan `components/*/src/**/*.clj` and `bases/*/src/**/*.clj`. For each `(throw ...)`, `(ex-info ...)`, `IllegalArgumentException.`, `RuntimeException.`, `(throw+ ...)` (slingshot):\n\n1. Extract the namespace of the file containing the form.\n2. If the namespace matches one of the **boundary patterns** above → skip.\n3. If the form is inside a `case`/`condp` default branch and the message contains \"unknown\" or \"unsupported\" → flag as `:fatal-only` (warning-only, can be dismissed).\n4. Otherwise → emit a `:warning` with file:line:col, the offending form, and the suggested anomaly-return rewrite (link to the example in this rule).\n\nOutput format follows the existing `bb review` convention. Severity defaults to `:warning`, not `:error` — there are legitimate exceptions; we want to surface, not hard-block. Promotion to `:error` happens per-repo after that repo's cleanup completes.\n\n## Related rules\n\n- `foundations/result-handling.mdc` (003) — the success/failure result-map shape and predicates\n- `foundations/validation-boundaries.mdc` (004) — *where* validation occurs (interface boundaries + external entry)\n- `foundations/stratified-design.mdc` (001) — layer discipline; this rule's \"boundary\" concept depends on layer hygiene\n\n## Reference component\n\nThe canonical implementation of the anomaly shape and constructor lives in miniforge OSS as the `ai.miniforge.anomaly` Polylith component (Apache 2). It exposes `anomaly`, `anomaly?`, the `Anomaly` malli schema, and the `anomaly-types` set. miniforge-family Clojure repos consume it via the existing vendoring relationship with miniforge.\n\nRepos that do not vendor miniforge may implement the same shape locally; the rule applies regardless of where the constructor lives, because the rule is about the discipline (return data, don't throw) rather than the specific namespace.",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/exceptions-as-data,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "005",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (005): Exceptions are data — return anomalies in normal flows; throw only at absolute boundaries"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Fulcro standards — queries, idents, normalisation, mutations, loads, domain naming",
               :agent-behavior
               "Fulcro is the default for stateful product UI in any miniforge web\nsurface that opts into Fulcro per `frameworks/web-architecture-mode.mdc`\nWEB-002. This rule extracts the load-bearing patterns from the\n*Fulcro Developer's Guide* (https://book.fulcrologic.com/) into\nenforceable repository rules. Every rule here traces to the Book;\ncite the section in PR review when the rule is non-obvious.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :audit,
                :message
                "Standard: Fulcro standards — queries, idents, normalisation, mutations, loads, domain naming"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:review :plan :implement},
                :file-globs ["**/*.cljs" "**/*.cljc"]},
               :severity :minor,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Fulcro standards\n\nFulcro is the default for stateful product UI in any miniforge web\nsurface that opts into Fulcro per `frameworks/web-architecture-mode.mdc`\nWEB-002. This rule extracts the load-bearing patterns from the\n*Fulcro Developer's Guide* (https://book.fulcrologic.com/) into\nenforceable repository rules. Every rule here traces to the Book;\ncite the section in PR review when the rule is non-obvious.\n\n## When Fulcro applies\n\nFulcro is for product UI involving durable entities, graph\nrelationships, workflow state, or policy / evidence interactions\n(per WEB-002).\n\n### FUL-001 — Use Fulcro for entity/workflow product UI\n\nIf a page renders durable entities (repositories, workflow runs, policy\npacks, evidence bundles, agents, approvals, etc.) or transitions\nworkflow state, it SHOULD be a Fulcro component tree. Static\ninformational pages stay server-rendered.\n\n## Component basics — queries, idents, initial state\n\nThe four-tuple `query` + `ident` + `initial-state` + `render` is the\nload-bearing contract. Get this right and the rest of the framework\nbehaves; get it wrong and you fight normalisation forever.\n\n### FUL-002 — Components must declare queries\n\nComponents that render application data MUST declare an explicit\n`:query`. Do not pass large opaque maps through component trees when\nthe component can declare its own data requirements.\n\n### FUL-003 — Use `comp/get-query` for joins\n\nParent component queries MUST use `comp/get-query` when joining to\nchild components.\n\n```clojure\n(defsc WorkflowList [_ {:list/keys [runs]}]\n  {:query [{:list/runs (comp/get-query WorkflowRun)}]\n   :ident :list/id\n   :initial-state {:list/id :workflow-list :list/runs []}}\n  ...)\n```\n\n`get-query` carries the metadata Fulcro needs for normalisation;\nhand-writing a child query inline breaks it.\n\n### FUL-004 — Persistent entities must have idents\n\nComponents representing persistent entities MUST define a stable\n`:ident`. Idents are the address into the normalised client DB.\n\nTypical persistent entity examples in a miniforge product UI:\n\n- repository / project / workspace\n- workflow run / step\n- policy pack / rule\n- evidence bundle / item\n- agent / job / task\n- approval / review\n- user / principal\n\nUI-only \"presence\" components (modals, panels, banners) do not need\nidents.\n\n### FUL-005 — Initial state must match UI shape\n\nInitial state SHOULD match the component tree shape and normalise\ncleanly. Root initial state SHOULD compose child initial state via\n`comp/get-initial-state`, not duplicate it manually.\n\n## Naming and key conventions\n\n### FUL-014 — Prefer domain-namespaced keywords\n\nApplication keys MUST be namespaced by domain.\n\n```clojure\n;; GOOD\n:repo/id :repo/name\n:workflow.run/id :workflow.run/status\n:policy.pack/id :evidence.bundle/id\n\n;; BAD — generic, ambiguous, collision-prone\n:id :name :status\n```\n\n### FUL-015 — UI-only state uses `:ui/*`\n\nUI-only state MUST use the `:ui/` namespace (or an equivalent explicit\nUI namespace).\n\n```clojure\n:ui/expanded?     :ui/selected-tab\n:ui/filter-text   :ui/modal-open?\n```\n\n### FUL-016 — Do not persist UI state accidentally\n\nServer writes MUST NOT persist `:ui/*` state unless explicitly\nintended. Strip `:ui/*` keys from mutation payloads before remote\nreturn.\n\n### FUL-029 — Do not leak database schema directly into UI\n\nFulcro entity keys SHOULD represent product / domain concepts, not raw\nstorage implementation details. `:repo/integration-status` is good;\n`:db/repos.integration_status_enum_value` is not.\n\n### FUL-035 — Keep naming consistent across client and server\n\nEntity names, ids, resolver names, and mutation names SHOULD use a\nshared domain vocabulary across CLJS, CLJC, and CLJ.\n\nEach consuming repo SHOULD declare its canonical domain nouns once (in\na shared `domain.cljc` or equivalent) and reference them across CLJS,\nCLJC, and CLJ namespaces. Common miniforge domain shapes include\nrepository, workflow run / step, policy pack / check, evidence bundle,\napproval, agent, integration.\n\n## Normalisation discipline\n\n### FUL-006 — Normalize server data\n\nServer responses intended for Fulcro app state SHOULD be normalisable\nentity graphs (i.e. each entity carries its ident-key, references are\nident-shaped). Avoid returning UI-specific denormalised blobs for\ndurable product state.\n\n### FUL-019 — Treat the client DB as a normalised database\n\nAfter normalisation, do not reason about state as a nested\ncomponent-owned object tree. Entity updates target normalised table\nentries by ident.\n\n### FUL-020 — Do not duplicate entity facts across tables\n\nA durable fact about an entity SHOULD have one canonical location. If a\nvalue appears in multiple UI contexts, render it from the same\nnormalised entity — do not copy.\n\n### FUL-018 — Use unions for polymorphic graph edges\n\nWhen a graph edge can point to different entity types, use Fulcro\nunion queries.\n\nCommon candidates: evidence-item variants, policy-result variants,\nworkflow-step variants, activity-feed events.\n\n## Mutations\n\n### FUL-007 — Mutations are the only state-transition boundary\n\nApplication state changes MUST flow through Fulcro mutations (or\napproved Fulcro mechanisms — load merges, refresh, deferred routing).\nDo NOT mutate app state ad hoc from rendering code, callbacks, or\nforeign JS wrappers.\n\n### FUL-008 — Mutations must be intent-named\n\nMutation names SHOULD describe domain intent, not implementation\ndetail.\n\n| Good | Bad |\n|---|---|\n| `workflow/start!` | `set-flag!` |\n| `policy-pack/activate!` | `update-map!` |\n| `evidence/mark-reviewed!` | `do-click!` |\n| `repo.integration/remove!` | `handle-button!` |\n\n### FUL-009 — Separate local and remote mutation effects\n\nMutations SHOULD clearly separate local optimistic effects from remote\neffects. A mutation with remote effects MUST define its expected\nfailure behaviour (rollback, error message, retry policy).\n\n### FUL-010 — Use transactions for user-driven operations\n\nUser-driven operations SHOULD be modelled as Fulcro transactions\n(`comp/transact!`). The UI submits intent; the mutation decides local\nand remote effects.\n\n### FUL-021 — Use targeted refresh\n\nMutations SHOULD refresh only the affected UI / data where practical.\nAvoid full app refreshes for changes scoped to a small entity set.\n\n### FUL-023 — Destructive mutations require domain-level confirmation\n\nA Fulcro mutation that performs a destructive remote effect MUST\nrequire prior UI confirmation appropriate to blast radius (per\n`languages/javascript.mdc` JS-007 and `frameworks/browser-security.mdc`\nBSEC-004). The confirmation belongs in the UI flow that *triggers* the\nmutation, not inside the mutation body.\n\n## Loads and remote interaction\n\n### FUL-012 — Use loads for remote reads\n\nRemote data reads SHOULD use Fulcro load mechanisms (`df/load!` or\nequivalent) rather than arbitrary `fetch` calls embedded in components.\n\n### FUL-013 — Loading and error state must be modelled\n\nRemote interactions MUST expose loading and error state in the UI\n(typically via load markers or per-entity status fields). Hidden\nspinners and silent failures are violations.\n\nError state SHOULD include enough diagnostic information to support\nevidence / debug workflows (request id, timestamp, error class,\nretryability hint).\n\n### FUL-028 — Server API should match graph needs\n\nThe server data API SHOULD support Fulcro graph reads and mutations\ncleanly. Pathom SHOULD be considered for graph-oriented server\nreads / resolvers. The internal Pathom / EQL surface is API class 1\n(per `frameworks/api-surface-classes.mdc`); the existing flat JSON\nendpoints stay alive as class-2 surfaces alongside it.\n\n## Render discipline\n\n### FUL-011 — No side effects in render\n\nComponent render bodies MUST NOT perform side effects.\n\nForbidden in render:\n- network calls\n- app state mutation\n- timers\n- subscriptions\n- DOM mutation outside React / Fulcro integration points\n\nMove side effects to mutation `:action`s, lifecycle hooks, or load\ncalls triggered by route / mutation events.\n\n### FUL-017 — Component queries are minimal and local\n\nEach component's query SHOULD request only the data it renders or\npasses to declared children. Avoid broad root queries that bypass\ncomponent composition.\n\n### FUL-024 — Components small but not anaemic\n\nA component SHOULD own:\n\n- its query\n- its ident if entity-backed\n- its initial state if applicable\n- its rendering\n- local UI event submission\n\nSplitting components so aggressively that query ownership becomes\nunclear is its own anti-pattern.\n\n### FUL-025 — Business rules out of CSS / DOM state\n\nFulcro logic MUST NOT infer domain truth from CSS classes, DOM\nattributes, or visual state. The data model is the source of truth;\nthe DOM reflects the data model.\n\n### FUL-033 — Avoid huge root components\n\nRoot components SHOULD compose major screen areas and routing, not\ncontain all product rendering logic.\n\n### FUL-034 — Prefer declarative screen composition\n\nScreens SHOULD be composed from queried components rather than\nmanually extracting arbitrary nested data in root-level rendering.\n\n## Workflow / domain modelling\n\n### FUL-022 — Model workflow state explicitly\n\nWorkflow state in the application MUST be explicit in the data model.\nTypical shape:\n\n- `:workflow.run/status`\n- `:workflow.run/current-step`\n- `:workflow.step/status`\n- `:workflow.step/error`\n- `:workflow.step/retryable?`\n\nOperational truth must NOT be derived only from incidental UI flags.\n\n### FUL-027 — Prefer CLJC for shared domain logic\n\nValidation, normalisation helpers, domain predicates, and\npolicy-adjacent logic SHOULD live in CLJC when shared by client and\nserver. Keeps the domain vocabulary single-sourced (FUL-035).\n\n### FUL-030 — Route state is product state when it controls workflow\n\nRoute parameters that control workflow / evidence / policy context\nSHOULD be treated as part of application state, normalised, and\ntested.\n\n## Interop and tooling\n\n### FUL-026 — JS / React interop is isolated\n\nJavaScript / React interop MUST be wrapped in small boundary\ncomponents. Interop components SHOULD expose Fulcro-friendly props\nand events; the rest of the system MUST NOT see the foreign API.\n\n### FUL-031 — Use Fulcro Inspect in development\n\nMiniforge Fulcro applications SHOULD support Fulcro Inspect during\ndevelopment. The build should not strip the integration in dev mode.\n\n### FUL-032 — Tests cover mutations and graph updates\n\nTests SHOULD verify:\n\n- mutation state transitions\n- normalised DB updates\n- remote mutation behaviour\n- load result normalisation\n- critical route transitions\n- failure states\n\nComponent render tests are useful but secondary; the data-model layer\nis where regressions hurt most.\n\n## Severity guidance\n\n| Severity | Examples |\n|---|---|\n| **blocker** | side effects in render (FUL-011); state changes outside mutations (FUL-007); destructive mutation without confirmation (FUL-023); domain truth inferred from DOM (FUL-025) |\n| **major** | persistent entity without ident (FUL-004); duplicated entity facts across tables (FUL-020); generic-keyed durable state (FUL-014); inline `fetch` instead of load (FUL-012) |\n| **minor** | non-intent-named mutation (FUL-008); broad root query (FUL-017); huge root component (FUL-033) |\n| **advisory** | could use a union (FUL-018); could move helper to CLJC (FUL-027) |\n\n## Agent behaviour\n\nWhen writing or reviewing Fulcro code:\n1. Open the four-tuple check on every `defsc` rendering data — `:query`,\n   `:ident` (if entity), `:initial-state` (if joined from root),\n   render. Missing pieces are the most common agent failure mode.\n2. For every mutation, confirm: intent-named (FUL-008), local vs\n   remote effects separated (FUL-009), destructive ones gated\n   (FUL-023).\n3. Grep for `fetch(`, `.then(`, `XMLHttpRequest` — each is a likely\n   FUL-012 violation.\n4. Grep for `:id`, `:name`, `:status` as bare keys in app-state\n   contexts — likely FUL-014 violations.\n5. When in doubt about a Fulcro idiom, cite the *Fulcro Developer's\n   Guide* section by number in the PR comment, not framework folklore.",
               :id :std/fulcro,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "340",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (340): Fulcro standards — queries, idents, normalisation, mutations, loads, domain naming"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Fulcro RAD — optional, for conventional CRUD/forms/reports; never forced onto bespoke workflow UI",
               :agent-behavior
               "Fulcro RAD (Rapid Application Development; see\nhttps://book.fulcrologic.com/RAD.html) is an *attribute-driven* layer\non top of Fulcro for CRUD-shaped surfaces. RAD is **optional** —\nuseful for conventional admin forms and reports, harmful when forced\nonto bespoke workflow surfaces.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :audit,
                :message
                "Standard: Fulcro RAD — optional, for conventional CRUD/forms/reports; never forced onto bespoke workflow UI"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:review :plan :implement},
                :file-globs ["**/*.cljs" "**/*.cljc"]},
               :severity :minor,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Fulcro RAD standards\n\nFulcro RAD (Rapid Application Development; see\nhttps://book.fulcrologic.com/RAD.html) is an *attribute-driven* layer\non top of Fulcro for CRUD-shaped surfaces. RAD is **optional** —\nuseful for conventional admin forms and reports, harmful when forced\nonto bespoke workflow surfaces.\n\nThis rule sits alongside `frameworks/fulcro.mdc` (which always\napplies to CLJS / CLJC). RAD adds rules; it does not replace any\nFulcro rule.\n\n## RAD-001 — RAD is optional\n\nFulcro RAD MAY be used where it reduces boilerplate without hiding\nimportant product behaviour. RAD is never required; a hand-written\nFulcro screen is always a valid choice.\n\n## RAD-002 — Use RAD for conventional forms and reports\n\nRAD SHOULD be considered for:\n\n- CRUD-like admin forms\n- tabular reports\n- attribute-driven forms\n- conventional entity management surfaces (list / detail / edit)\n\nThese shapes have well-defined RAD generators that pay back the\nlearning cost.\n\n## RAD-003 — Do not force RAD onto bespoke workflow UIs\n\nRAD SHOULD NOT be forced onto highly custom workflow-control surfaces\nwhere explicit Fulcro components are clearer.\n\nExamples that belong in bespoke Fulcro, not RAD:\n\n- live workflow execution graph\n- PR train visualisation\n- evidence bundle diff / review\n- policy failure triage\n- agent orchestration console\n- recommendation + control panel\n\nWhen the surface is more bespoke than CRUD, the RAD ergonomics fight\nthe design rather than helping.\n\n## RAD-004 — Attribute definitions are domain contracts\n\nRAD attributes, when used, SHOULD be treated as domain model contracts\nand reviewed as carefully as a database schema migration. Renaming or\nre-typing an attribute is a breaking change.\n\nAttribute names follow the same domain-vocabulary rule as\n`frameworks/fulcro.mdc` FUL-035. RAD attribute namespaces match the\nFulcro entity namespaces (`:repo/...`, `:workflow.run/...`, etc.).\n\n## RAD-005 — Escape hatch required\n\nAny RAD usage MUST preserve the ability to drop to custom Fulcro UI\nwhere product behaviour requires it. A surface that is \"100% RAD with\nno escape\" is a code smell — when the requirements move beyond RAD's\ngenerators, you cannot incrementally take over rendering or mutation.\n\nConcretely: each RAD-generated screen SHOULD be wrapped or composed\nsuch that a hand-written Fulcro replacement can be slotted in without\nrewriting the surrounding routing and state.\n\n## Agent behaviour\n\nWhen asked to add a CRUD-shaped surface:\n1. Classify the surface against RAD-002 / RAD-003. If bespoke, use\n   plain Fulcro per `frameworks/fulcro.mdc`.\n2. If RAD is the right fit, declare the attribute set in a\n   shared CLJC namespace (per FUL-027) so the contract is single-sourced.\n3. Confirm the escape hatch (RAD-005) before merging — name the\n   replacement strategy in the PR description if the surface looks\n   likely to outgrow RAD.",
               :id :std/fulcro-rad,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "341",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (341): Fulcro RAD — optional, for conventional CRUD/forms/reports; never forced onto bespoke workflow UI"}
