               :severity :minor,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Rules Catalog (Dewey-style)\n\n## Classification System\n\nUses Dewey Decimal principles: hierarchical, numeric, extensible.\nDewey codes live in frontmatter (`dewey: \"NNN\"`), not filenames or paths.\n\n| Range | Category | Description |\n|-------|----------|-------------|\n| 000-099 | Foundations | Architecture, design philosophy, core principles |\n| 100-199 | Tools | Linters, formatters, build tools |\n| 200-299 | Languages | Language-specific conventions |\n| 300-399 | Frameworks | Platform & framework rules |\n| 400-499 | Testing | Testing standards & quality |\n| 500-599 | Operations | CI/CD, monitoring, security |\n| 600-699 | Documentation | Docs standards |\n| 700-799 | Workflows | Git, PR, release processes |\n| 800-899 | Project | Reserved for project-specific |\n| 900-999 | Meta | Templates, indexes, deprecated |\n\n## Directory Structure\n\n```\n<repo-root>/                             # consumed as .standards/ submodule\n├── index.mdc                            # This catalog (dewey: \"000\")\n├── foundations/\n│   ├── stratified-design.mdc                 # dewey: \"001\"  alwaysApply: true\n│   ├── code-quality.mdc                      # dewey: \"002\"  alwaysApply: true\n│   ├── result-handling.mdc                   # dewey: \"003\"  alwaysApply: true\n│   ├── validation-boundaries.mdc             # dewey: \"004\"  alwaysApply: true\n│   ├── exceptions-as-data.mdc                # dewey: \"005\"  alwaysApply: true\n│   ├── simple-made-easy.mdc                  # dewey: \"010\"  alwaysApply: true\n│   ├── specification-standards.mdc           # dewey: \"020\"\n│   ├── work-spec-authoring.mdc               # dewey: \"021\"\n│   ├── runtime-no-host-docker-socket.mdc     # dewey: \"030\"  alwaysApply: true\n│   ├── runtime-require-rootless.mdc          # dewey: \"031\"  alwaysApply: true\n│   ├── runtime-restrict-host-mounts.mdc      # dewey: \"032\"  alwaysApply: true\n│   ├── runtime-require-image-digest-pin.mdc  # dewey: \"033\"  alwaysApply: true\n│   └── localization.mdc                      # dewey: \"050\"  alwaysApply: true\n├── languages/\n│   ├── clojure.mdc                      # dewey: \"210\"  alwaysApply: true\n│   ├── clojure-exception-handling.mdc   # dewey: \"211\"  alwaysApply: true\n│   ├── python.mdc                       # dewey: \"220\"\n│   ├── rust.mdc                         # dewey: \"230\"\n│   ├── swift.mdc                        # dewey: \"240\"\n│   ├── javascript.mdc                   # dewey: \"250\"\n│   ├── css.mdc                          # dewey: \"260\"\n│   └── html.mdc                         # dewey: \"270\"\n├── frameworks/\n│   ├── polylith.mdc                     # dewey: \"310\"\n│   ├── polylith-composition.mdc         # dewey: \"311\"\n│   ├── polylith-tool.mdc                # dewey: \"312\"\n│   ├── kubernetes.mdc                   # dewey: \"320\"\n│   ├── web-architecture-mode.mdc        # dewey: \"330\"\n│   ├── browser-security.mdc             # dewey: \"331\"\n│   ├── api-surface-classes.mdc          # dewey: \"332\"\n│   ├── fulcro.mdc                       # dewey: \"340\"\n│   └── fulcro-rad.mdc                   # dewey: \"341\"\n├── testing/\n│   └── standards.mdc                    # dewey: \"400\"  alwaysApply: true\n├── workflows/\n│   ├── git-branch-management.mdc        # dewey: \"710\"\n│   ├── pre-commit-discipline.mdc        # dewey: \"715\"  alwaysApply: true\n│   ├── pr-documentation.mdc             # dewey: \"721\"\n│   ├── pr-layering.mdc                  # dewey: \"722\"  alwaysApply: true\n│   ├── git-worktrees.mdc                # dewey: \"725\"\n│   └── datever.mdc                      # dewey: \"730\"\n├── project/\n│   └── header-copyright.mdc             # dewey: \"810\"  alwaysApply: true\n└── meta/\n    └── rule-format.mdc                  # dewey: \"900\"\n```\n\n## Current Rules\n\n### foundations/\n\n| Dewey | File | Always | Description |\n|-------|------|--------|-------------|\n| 001 | `stratified-design` | ✓ | One-way DAG dependencies, layered architecture |\n| 002 | `code-quality` | ✓ | Composable pipelines, no nested conditionals, DRY |\n| 003 | `result-handling` | ✓ | success?/failed? predicates; schema constructors |\n| 004 | `validation-boundaries` | ✓ | Schemas at interface/external boundaries only |\n| 005 | `exceptions-as-data` | ✓ | Anomalies as data in flows; throw only at absolute boundaries |\n| 010 | `simple-made-easy` | ✓ | Simplicity over familiarity, uncomplected artifacts |\n| 020 | `specification-standards` |  | Normative specs (N1-N6), spec governance, conformance |\n| 021 | `work-spec-authoring` |  | `work/*.spec.edn` format: priority, theme, normative-refs, testable acceptance criteria |\n| 030 | `runtime-no-host-docker-socket` | ✓ | Reject bind mounts of `/var/run/docker.sock` and equivalents (capsule isolation) |\n| 031 | `runtime-require-rootless` | ✓ | Warn / hard-stop based on the runtime's `:rootless` capability |\n| 032 | `runtime-restrict-host-mounts` | ✓ | Review host bind mounts outside an allowlist |\n| 033 | `runtime-require-image-digest-pin` | ✓ | Reject execution plans whose `:image-digest` is not `sha256:<64-hex>` |\n| 050 | `localization` | ✓ | No raw strings in views; msg/t + en-US.edn always |\n\n### languages/\n\n| Dewey | File | Always | Description |\n|-------|------|--------|-------------|\n| 210 | `clojure` | ✓ | Polylith + per-file stratified design, map access patterns |\n| 211 | `clojure-exception-handling` | ✓ | Prefer slingshot `try+` / `throw+` (strict superset of `try`); plain `try` allowed in three narrow cases (no-slingshot-dep leaf catch, leaf inside `try+`, REPL/`(comment …)`) |\n| 220 | `python` |  | Poetry, functional Python |\n| 230 | `rust` |  | Workspaces, typed boundary commands, pipeline selection, data-driven content |\n| 240 | `swift` |  | Swift conventions |\n| 250 | `javascript` |  | Browser JS — sparse use, no globals, ES modules, no inline handlers, safe DOM |\n| 260 | `css` |  | Design tokens, semantic class names, shallow selectors, accessible focus |\n| 270 | `html` |  | Semantic elements, buttons-vs-links, labelled forms |\n\n### frameworks/\n\n| Dewey | File | Always | Description |\n|-------|------|--------|-------------|\n| 310 | `polylith` |  | Polylith workspace conventions |\n| 311 | `polylith-composition` |  | Brick-oriented production code, interface contracts, validation gates, change-derived CI scope |\n| 312 | `polylith-tool` |  | Polylith as an architectural control tool — preflight reasoning, canonical workflow, agent-role operational requirements |\n| 320 | `kubernetes` |  | K8s/Kustomize/ArgoCD conventions |\n| 330 | `web-architecture-mode` |  | Fulcro for stateful UI, server HTML for simple pages, no new browser fw without ADR |\n| 331 | `browser-security` |  | Server-enforced authz, CSRF, no secrets in browser, blast-radius UI |\n| 332 | `api-surface-classes` |  | Internal (EDN/Transit) vs first-party cross-language (JSON/SSE) vs customer extension (REST/webhooks) |\n| 340 | `fulcro` |  | Queries, idents, normalisation, mutations, loads, domain naming |\n| 341 | `fulcro-rad` |  | RAD optional for CRUD/forms; never forced onto bespoke workflow UI |\n\n### testing/\n\n| Dewey | File | Always | Description |\n|-------|------|--------|-------------|\n| 400 | `standards` | ✓ | Factory functions, same standards as production code |\n\n### workflows/\n\n| Dewey | File | Always | Description |\n|-------|------|--------|-------------|\n| 710 | `git-branch-management` |  | Branch from main, single-purpose PRs |\n| 715 | `pre-commit-discipline` | ✓ | Never bypass hooks without investigation; fix root causes |\n| 721 | `pr-documentation` |  | Living PR docs in `docs/pull-requests/` |\n| 722 | `pr-layering` | ✓ | Stratified PR DAG; <400 lines; independently mergeable |\n| 725 | `git-worktrees` |  | Parallel workflows with worktrees, operator multi-loop |\n| 730 | `datever` |  | Date-based versioning strategy |\n\n### project/\n\n| Dewey | File | Always | Description |\n|-------|------|--------|-------------|\n| 810 | `header-copyright` | ✓ | Miniforge.ai header + copyright ownership |\n\n### meta/\n\n| Dewey | File | Always | Description |\n|-------|------|--------|-------------|\n| 900 | `rule-format` |  | Rule creation template & Dewey classification |\n\n## Adding Rules\n\n1. Find the appropriate Dewey category above\n2. Create `<category>/<slug>.mdc` with `dewey: \"NNN\"` in frontmatter\n3. Set `alwaysApply: true` if the rule should be pre-injected into every agent prompt\n4. Update this index and `CLAUDE.md`",
               :id :std/index,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "000",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (000): Master index of all rules — consult when searching for applicable rules"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Browser JavaScript — sparse use, no global state, ES modules, no inline handlers, safe DOM",
               :agent-behavior
               "JavaScript in any miniforge web surface is a *progressive enhancement*\ntool, not an application-architecture substrate. Stateful product UI\nbelongs in Fulcro (`frameworks/fulcro.mdc`), not in JS modules.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :audit,
                :message
                "Standard: Browser JavaScript — sparse use, no global state, ES modules, no inline handlers, safe DOM"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:review :implement},
                :file-globs ["**/*.js" "**/*.mjs"]},
               :severity :minor,
               :knowledge-content
               "# JavaScript (browser) standards\n\nJavaScript in any miniforge web surface is a *progressive enhancement*\ntool, not an application-architecture substrate. Stateful product UI\nbelongs in Fulcro (`frameworks/fulcro.mdc`), not in JS modules.\n\n## JS-001 — Use JavaScript sparingly\n\nPlain JavaScript is for progressive enhancement or isolated widgets only.\n\n| Acceptable | Not acceptable |\n|---|---|\n| menu toggles | application state machines |\n| copy-to-clipboard | multi-entity editing flows |\n| small form enhancement | client routing |\n| simple websocket event display | normalised data caches |\n| local filtering / sorting | optimistic UI for remote ops |\n\nAnything in the not-acceptable column belongs in Fulcro.\n\n## JS-002 — No global application state\n\nApplication state MUST NOT live on `window` or unstructured globals.\n\n```js\n// BAD\nwindow.currentWorkflow = workflow;\nwindow.userState = state;\n\n// GOOD — module-local, scoped, explicit\nconst moduleState = { selected: null };\nexport function setSelected(x) { moduleState.selected = x; }\n```\n\nAcceptable:\n- module-local state inside an ES module\n- isolated per-widget state captured in a closure or class instance\n- explicit named state objects scoped to one module\n\n## JS-003 — Use ES modules\n\nNew JavaScript MUST be authored as ES modules and loaded with\n`<script type=\"module\">`.\n\n```html\n<script type=\"module\" src=\"/assets/app.js\"></script>\n```\n\nNo `var`, no IIFE wrappers, no UMD bundles for new code.\n\n## JS-004 — No inline event handlers\n\nHTML MUST NOT use `onclick=`, `onchange=`, etc. Bind in JS using\n`addEventListener` against a `data-action` selector.\n\n```html\n<!-- BAD -->\n<button onclick=\"deleteRepo()\">Delete</button>\n\n<!-- GOOD -->\n<button data-action=\"delete-repo\">Delete</button>\n```\n\n```js\ndocument\n  .querySelector('[data-action=\"delete-repo\"]')\n  .addEventListener('click', onDeleteRepo);\n```\n\n## JS-005 — Bind behaviour with `data-*`, not visual classes\n\nBehavioural selectors MUST use semantic `data-*` attributes. JS MUST NOT\nselect on visual class names — those are CSS's contract, not JS's.\n\n```js\n// BAD\ndocument.querySelector('.blue-button');\n\n// GOOD\ndocument.querySelector('[data-action=\"copy-token\"]');\n```\n\n## JS-006 — Async operations need visible states\n\nAny browser-triggered network operation MUST surface four states to the\nuser: **idle, pending, success, failure**.\n\nFailures MUST be visible (not silently swallowed, not console-only). The\nvisual treatment for each state SHOULD be consistent across the surface\n(e.g. a `data-state` attribute the CSS keys off of).\n\n## JS-007 — Guard destructive actions\n\nDestructive actions MUST require confirmation, undo, or typed\nconfirmation, scaled to blast radius:\n\n| Blast radius | Guard |\n|---|---|\n| local UI dismiss | none |\n| revoke a session | confirm dialog |\n| cancel a workflow run | confirm dialog |\n| delete a policy pack | typed-name confirmation |\n| revoke a credential | typed-name confirmation + audit notice |\n| approve a destructive infra change | typed confirmation + blast-radius preview |\n\nSee `frameworks/browser-security.mdc` BSEC-004 for the\nblast-radius-preview requirement.\n\n## JS-008 — Do not inject untrusted HTML\n\nJS MUST NOT assign server-sourced or user-sourced content to the\n`innerHTML`, `outerHTML`, or `insertAdjacentHTML` sinks. These are\nunconditional XSS surfaces.\n\nFor text content, use the `textContent` property:\n\n```js\n// GOOD\nel.textContent = response.message;\n```\n\nFor structured markup, build the tree explicitly with\n`document.createElement` + `appendChild`, or use a `<template>` element\nwith text-only insertion points.\n\n### Sanitiser escape hatch\n\nIf a sanitizer is genuinely required (e.g. rendering trusted Markdown\nto HTML), the use MUST satisfy ALL of:\n\n1. Sanitization goes through a single vetted library (DOMPurify or\n   equivalent) with a default-deny configuration.\n2. The sanitizer call lives in ONE boundary module per repo, named\n   `safe-html` or similar; no other module touches `innerHTML`.\n3. The boundary module exports only `setSanitisedHTML(el, source)` —\n   no raw `innerHTML` setter is exposed.\n4. The boundary module's allow-list (tags, attributes, URL schemes) is\n   reviewed in the PR that introduces it and in any PR that widens it.\n\nReject any PR that introduces a write to `innerHTML` *outside* the\nboundary module, or that widens the boundary module's allow-list\nwithout explicit reviewer sign-off.\n\n## Agent behaviour\n\nWhen writing or reviewing browser JS:\n1. If the change introduces durable client state, multi-entity editing,\n   or workflow state → escalate to Fulcro per `frameworks/web-architecture-mode.mdc`\n   WEB-002.\n2. Grep for `window.<name> =` and `onclick=` / `on*=` in HTML and JS;\n   each is a violation of JS-002 / JS-004.\n3. Grep for the `innerHTML` sink — every hit needs justification or\n   rewrite to `textContent` per JS-008.\n4. Reject any new module that reaches into another module's state via\n   globals.",
               :id :std/javascript,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "250",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (250): Browser JavaScript — sparse use, no global state, ES modules, no inline handlers, safe DOM"}
        #:rule{:title "K8s/Kustomize/ArgoCD conventions",
               :agent-behavior
               "- **Always switch to the appropriate Kubernetes cluster context before running kubectl commands**\n- Use `kubectl config use-context <context-name>` to switch environments\n- Verify current context with `kubectl config current-context` before proceeding",
               :enforcement
               {:action :audit,
                :message "Standard: K8s/Kustomize/ArgoCD conventions"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:review :plan :implement},
                :file-globs
                ["k8s/**/*.yaml" "**/overlays/**/**/*.yaml"]},
               :severity :minor,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Kubernetes, Kustomize, ArgoCD conventions\n\n## Environment Context (ALWAYS)\n\n- **Always switch to the appropriate Kubernetes cluster context before running kubectl commands**\n- Use `kubectl config use-context <context-name>` to switch environments\n- Verify current context with `kubectl config current-context` before proceeding\n\n## General guidelines\n\n### ArgoCD\n\n- App-of-Apps per env; image tags tracked in overlay patches.\n- Avoid “going backwards”: pin to immutable tag in manifests, change via PR.\n\n### Kustomize\n\n- Kustomize layout: /k8s/base and /k8s/overlays/{local,nonprod,prod}\n\n#### Kustomize Patching\n\n- **Patch only differences**: Only patch fields that actually differ between environments\n- **Strategic merge over JSON patches**: Use strategic merge for multiple resources of same type\n- **Minimal patch scope**: Don't patch metadata labels unless used for selection/monitoring\n- **Base + patches pattern**: Move common structure to base, patch only environment-specific values\n- **Avoid duplication**: If 90%+ of a resource is identical across environments, use base + patches\n\n#### Patch Design Checklist\n\n- [ ] Does this patch only change what actually differs between environments?\n- [ ] Are we patching metadata that serves no functional purpose?\n- [ ] Could this be simplified by moving more to the base?\n- [ ] Does the patch clearly show the intent (what changes per environment)?\n\n### K8s Networking\n\n- For Services: internal traffic uses ClusterIP; public via ALB ingress; no NodePort.\n- Ingress (AWS ALB): set `alb.ingress.kubernetes.io/scheme: internal|internet-facing` appropriately; HTTPS only; redirect 80→443.\n\n### Health Checks\n\n- Health:\n  - readiness: dependency-aware endpoint (auth optional)\n  - liveness: cheap, local check; avoid remote deps\n\n### Resource constraints\n\n- Resources: set realistic `requests/limits`; don’t copy placeholders.\n- Secrets:\n  - Prefer Secrets Store CSI for runtime; SealedSecrets for K8s-native secrets.",
               :id :std/kubernetes,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "320",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (320): K8s/Kustomize/ArgoCD conventions"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Localization — all user-facing strings via i18n resource files, no raw string literals",
               :agent-behavior
               "When writing or reviewing view/template code:\n1. Every string literal in a view namespace is a violation — replace with `(msg/t :key)`.\n2. When adding a new user-visible string, add the key to `en-US.edn` first, then reference it.\n3. When reviewing a PR, grep for string literals in `views/` or `templates/` namespaces — each is a missing l10n key.\n4. Format strings that combine a label + value use separate keys: `(str (msg/t :label) value)` not `(str \"Label: \" value)`.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message
                "Standard: Localization — all user-facing strings via i18n resource files, no raw string literals"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement}},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Localization (ALWAYS)\n\n**No raw string literals in views, templates, or user-facing output.** All user-visible text comes from a localization resource file.\n\n## The rule\n\nEvery string a user sees — labels, headings, error messages, button text, empty-state copy, units — must be looked up via the i18n system, not written inline.\n\n```clojure\n;; BAD — raw string literals in view code\n[:h3 \"No Workflows Yet\"]\n[:p \"Workflows will appear here when you run a workflow\"]\n[:button \"Pause\"]\n(str \"Duration: \" duration \"ms\")\n\n;; GOOD — keys resolved via i18n\n[:h3 (msg/t :workflow/none-heading)]\n[:p  (msg/t :workflow/none-body)]\n[:button (msg/t :cp/btn-pause)]\n(str (msg/t :metric/duration-prefix) duration (msg/t :duration/ms-suffix))\n```\n\n## en-US.edn is the canonical source\n\nThe primary resource file is `resources/config/web-dashboard/messages/en-US.edn` (or the equivalent `messages/en-US.edn` for the component). This is the canonical record of every user-visible string. New strings go here first.\n\n```edn\n;; en-US.edn — add new keys here\n{:web-dashboard/messages\n {:workflow/none-heading \"No Workflows Yet\"\n  :workflow/none-body    \"Workflows will appear here when you run a workflow\"\n  :workflow/none-hint    \"Try running a workflow to see real-time progress tracking.\"\n  :duration/ms-suffix    \"ms\"\n  :duration/s-suffix     \"s\"\n  :duration/min-suffix   \"m\"}}\n```\n\n## Key naming conventions\n\n- Namespace by component/feature: `:workflow/`, `:cp/`, `:metric/`\n- Use domain semantics, not UI position: `:workflow/none-heading` not `:sidebar/empty-title`\n- Suffixes: `-heading`, `-body`, `-hint`, `-label`, `-prefix`, `-suffix`, `-placeholder`\n- Error messages: `:error/<component>-<condition>` (e.g., `:error/agent-not-found`)\n\n## What requires localization\n\n| Category | Example | Requires l10n |\n|----------|---------|---------------|\n| UI labels | \"Pause\", \"Submit\", \"Cancel\" | Yes |\n| Headings and body copy | \"No agents registered\" | Yes |\n| Error messages shown to user | \"Agent not found\" | Yes |\n| Units and suffixes shown in UI | \"ms\", \"s\", \" tokens\" | Yes |\n| Placeholder / hint text | \"Type your response...\" | Yes |\n| Log messages (developer-facing) | \"Error reading file\" | No |\n| Code comments | | No |\n| Test assertions | | No |\n| EDN/config keys | | No |\n\n## Agent behavior\n\nWhen writing or reviewing view/template code:\n1. Every string literal in a view namespace is a violation — replace with `(msg/t :key)`.\n2. When adding a new user-visible string, add the key to `en-US.edn` first, then reference it.\n3. When reviewing a PR, grep for string literals in `views/` or `templates/` namespaces — each is a missing l10n key.\n4. Format strings that combine a label + value use separate keys: `(str (msg/t :label) value)` not `(str \"Label: \" value)`.\n\n## Anti-patterns to reject\n\n- Inline strings in Hiccup: `[:p \"Loading...\"]` — use `(msg/t :some/loading)`\n- String interpolation with hardcoded copy: `(str \"Error: \" msg)` — localize the prefix\n- `\"—\"` as a nil placeholder inline — use `(msg/t :time/none)` or equivalent\n- Format strings with embedded units: `(format \"%.1fs\" n)` — extract the `s` suffix\n- Duplicate strings across files — one key, referenced in multiple places",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/localization,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "050",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (050): Localization — all user-facing strings via i18n resource files, no raw string literals"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Apply Polylith architecture conventions for component organization and test placement",
               :agent-behavior
               "- **Bases** - Entry points (CLI, servers, API gateways)\n- **Components** - Reusable building blocks with clear interfaces\n- **Projects** - Deployable artifacts that compose bases + components\n- **Development** - Dev-time utilities, not deployed",
               :enforcement
               {:action :audit,
                :message
                "Standard: Apply Polylith architecture conventions for component organization and test placement"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:review :plan :implement},
                :file-globs
                ["components/**/*.clj"
                 "bases/**/*.clj"
                 "projects/**/*.clj"
                 "test/**/*.clj"]},
               :severity :minor,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Polylith Architecture Best Practices\n\n## Component Structure\n\n- **Bases** - Entry points (CLI, servers, API gateways)\n- **Components** - Reusable building blocks with clear interfaces\n- **Projects** - Deployable artifacts that compose bases + components\n- **Development** - Dev-time utilities, not deployed\n\n## Test Placement by Runtime ⏱️\n\n<critical>\nTests MUST be placed based on their runtime characteristics:\n\n- **< 100ms runtime** → Place in `components/<name>/test/` (unit tests)\n- **≥ 100ms runtime** → Place in `projects/<name>/test/` (integration tests)\n\nThis boundary typically aligns with:\n- Unit tests = fast, isolated, no I/O → bricks\n- Integration tests = slow, with I/O, dependencies → projects\n</critical>\n\n### Rationale\n\n- Pre-commit hooks run brick (component) tests only → must stay fast\n- CI runs full suite (`bb test:all`) → includes integration tests\n- Fast unit tests enable rapid local feedback loops\n- Integration tests verify cross-component behavior without slowing commits\n\n## Test Naming Conventions\n\n```clojure\n;; Unit tests (in components)\n(ns ai.miniforge.workflow.core-test)\n\n;; Integration tests (in projects)\n(ns ai.miniforge.workflow.configurable-integration-test)\n```\n\n<example>\n**Good**: Git operations test taking 300ms → `projects/miniforge/test/ai/miniforge/git_integration_test.clj`\n\n**Good**: Pure function validation taking 5ms → `components/workflow/test/ai/miniforge/workflow/core_test.clj`\n</example>\n\n<example type=\"invalid\">\n**Bad**: Datalevin database test in brick → causes pre-commit failures\n\n**Bad**: 200ms test in component → slows down every commit\n</example>\n\n## Interface-Driven Design\n\n- Each component exposes public API via `interface.clj`\n- Internal implementation in `core.clj` or domain-specific namespaces\n- Tests should primarily target the interface contract\n- Components depend only on other component interfaces, never internals\n\n## Unique Interface Names (CRITICAL)\n\n<critical>\n**Components MUST NOT overload the same interface name.** Each component has\nits own unique `:poly/interface`. Runtime backend swapping happens via\nmultimethod dispatch or adapter selection — NEVER by having two components\nclaim the same interface.\n</critical>\n\nPolylith profiles exist to bundle dev/test variants, **not** to work around\noverloaded interface names. If `poly check` reports Error 106 (multi-impl\ninterfaces), the fix is to rename interfaces, not to add a profile.\n\n### Correct patterns for \"multiple implementations\"\n\n**Pattern A — Multimethod dispatch inside a canonical interface component**\n\nOne component owns the canonical interface and a `(defmulti ... dispatch-fn)`.\nOther components register backend methods against that multimethod. Each\nbackend-provider component still has its OWN unique interface name.\n\n```\ncomponents/tool-pubsub/             interface: :tool-pubsub  (canonical + defmulti)\ncomponents/tool-pubsub-coreasync/   interface: :tool-pubsub-coreasync\ncomponents/adapter-pubsub-gcp/      interface: :adapter-pubsub\n```\n\nNo two components share `:poly/interface`. Projects pick which backend\ncomponent to include; runtime dispatch resolves the active implementation.\n\n**Pattern B — Adapter components with distinct interfaces**\n\nEach adapter exposes its own interface; a consumer depends on the interface\nit actually wants. Swapping happens by changing which adapter the project\nincludes, not by overloading.\n\n**Pattern C — Extension, not replacement**\n\nA specialization component (e.g., `phase-software-factory`) gets its OWN\ninterface (`:phase-software-factory`) and depends on the canonical\n`:phase` interface. It extends, rather than claiming to re-implement, the\nbase interface.\n\n<example type=\"invalid\">\n**Bad**: `phase`, `phase-deployment`, and `phase-software-factory` all declare\n`:poly/interface :phase` in their `deps.edn`. `poly check` reports Error 106.\nAdding a profile does not fix this — it hides the conflict.\n</example>\n\n<example>\n**Good**: `phase` keeps `:phase` and owns shared multimethods. `phase-deployment`\ndeclares `:phase-deployment`. `phase-software-factory` declares\n`:phase-software-factory`. Projects include whichever they need; `poly check`\nreports zero multi-impl errors.\n</example>\n\n## Build Tasks\n\n```bash\nbb test             # Unit tests only (bricks)\nbb test:integration # Project integration tests\nbb test:all         # Full suite (unit + integration)\n```",
               :id :std/polylith,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "310",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (310): Apply Polylith architecture conventions for component organization and test placement"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Enforce Polylith architectural integrity — bricks hold production logic, interfaces are contracts, validation gates workflows",
               :agent-behavior
               "Preserve Polylith architectural integrity by enforcing brick-oriented production\ncode, interface-based composition, boundary isolation in bases, and\nproject-context validation/testing. Polylith is not just a folder layout — it\nencodes an architectural model that only holds if components are reusable,\nbases are boundary adapters, interfaces are stable contracts, and workflows are\ngated by structural validation.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :audit,
                :message
                "Standard: Enforce Polylith architectural integrity — bricks hold production logic, interfaces are contracts, validation gates workflows"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:review :plan :implement},
                :file-globs
                ["components/**"
                 "bases/**"
                 "projects/**"
                 "development/**"
                 ".github/workflows/**"
                 "workspace.edn"
                 "deps.edn"]},
               :severity :minor,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Polylith Architecture and Composition (Rule `arch.polylith.structure-and-composition`)\n\n## Intent\n\nPreserve Polylith architectural integrity by enforcing brick-oriented production\ncode, interface-based composition, boundary isolation in bases, and\nproject-context validation/testing. Polylith is not just a folder layout — it\nencodes an architectural model that only holds if components are reusable,\nbases are boundary adapters, interfaces are stable contracts, and workflows are\ngated by structural validation.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Production code belongs in bricks\n\nProduction application logic MUST live in bases and components. Deployable\nprojects MUST NOT become general-purpose homes for production business logic.\n\n- Reusable business logic MUST be implemented in components.\n- Boundary and entrypoint logic MUST be implemented in bases.\n- Projects SHOULD primarily compose bricks and configure deployment/runtime concerns.\n\n<critical>\nDo NOT introduce production namespaces under `projects/*/src`. Do NOT use\nproject namespaces as a substitute for missing components. Do NOT duplicate\nproduction logic across projects instead of extracting a component.\n</critical>\n\n---\n\n## 2. Bases are boundary adapters\n\nA base MUST act as a bridge between the outside world and component interfaces.\n\nBases MAY own: application entrypoints, framework adapters, transport wiring,\nrequest/response translation, infrastructure-facing orchestration, side-effect\ninitiation at system boundaries.\n\n- Bases MUST delegate business behavior to components.\n- Bases SHOULD isolate framework-specific or runtime-specific concerns.\n\n<critical>\nBases MUST NOT become the primary home of reusable business logic. Bases MUST\nNOT depend on internals of other components. Bases MUST NOT be treated as\nshared libraries.\n</critical>\n\n---\n\n## 3. Components are accessed only through interfaces\n\nA component MUST be consumed through its interface namespace(s), not through\nits internal implementation namespaces. **This is an inviolable boundary.**\n\n- Cross-component calls MUST target interface namespaces only.\n- Component internals MAY change freely as long as interface contracts hold.\n- Interface namespaces SHOULD define a small, intentional public contract.\n\n<critical>\nNever reach into another brick's `src` namespaces. Never bypass an interface\nbecause it is \"simpler\" or \"faster\" during local development. Polylith's\n`poly check` Error 101 exists to catch this — it must pass.\n</critical>\n\n---\n\n## 4. Interfaces are contracts\n\nAn interface change MUST be treated as a contract change.\n\n- Interface changes SHOULD trigger broader review and impact analysis.\n- Compatibility-sensitive changes SHOULD be made explicit in review metadata.\n- Component public surface area SHOULD stay small and intentional.\n- Do NOT expose internal helpers as public interface for convenience.\n- Do NOT make silent interface changes without updating dependents.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Development code belongs in the development workspace\n\nScratch code, REPL support, exploratory integration, and temporary developer\nutilities SHOULD live under the `development/` workspace rather than being\nembedded in production bricks.\n\n- Experimental or workflow-driving dev code SHOULD start in `development/`.\n- Only promoted, intentional production code SHOULD move into bricks.\n- Do NOT leave temporary exploratory code inside production bricks.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Validation is a workflow gate\n\nWorkspace validation MUST succeed before deeper automation proceeds. A\nstructurally invalid workspace MUST stop downstream workflows.\n\n<critical>\n`poly check` (or equivalent structural validation) MUST pass before test,\nreview, release, or packaging workflows continue. Validation failures are\nhard failures, never informational warnings.\n</critical>\n\nPolicy pipelines SHOULD surface illegal dependencies and structural violations\nearly. Do NOT continue release preparation when validation fails.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Testing reflects project composition\n\nBrick tests MUST be evaluated in the context of the deployable projects that\ninclude those bricks. Testing only in local isolation is insufficient when\nthe shipped artifact is a project composition.\n\n- Brick tests MUST stay colocated with the brick they validate.\n- Test execution SHOULD reflect affected deployable project contexts.\n- Project-level tests SHOULD validate composed runtime behavior.\n\n**Prefer real composition over excessive mocking.** Mock only true externals,\nunstable boundaries, or impractical side effects. Use the workspace's\ncomposability to test integrated behavior directly where feasible.\n\nDo NOT rely exclusively on isolated unit tests when deployable composition is\nthe actual contract. Do NOT replace ordinary component collaboration with\nmocks by default.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Selective CI/release scope must be change-derived\n\nBuild, test, and release scope SHOULD be derived from changed and affected\nprojects relative to a **stable reference point** — a tag where the workspace\nwas known-good.\n\n- CI SHOULD use stable or release tags as comparison anchors.\n- Changed-or-affected projects SHOULD determine selective scope.\n- Do NOT deploy arbitrary project subsets without impact analysis.\n- Do NOT fall back to full-repo rebuilds when change analysis is available.\n- Do NOT use \"most recently touched file\" as a release heuristic.\n\n---\n\n## Enforcement\n\n### Hard-fail (errors)\n1. Production business logic introduced under `projects/*/src`.\n2. Cross-component dependency on non-interface namespaces (`poly check` Error 101).\n3. Validation failure prior to test/release workflow continuation.\n4. Illegal dependency edges between bricks.\n5. Release/build targeting that ignores changed-or-affected analysis where the workflow contract requires it.\n\n### Advisory (warnings, may escalate)\n1. Excessive domain logic in bases.\n2. Overgrown interfaces with convenience exports.\n3. High-mock tests where real composition is feasible.\n4. Exploratory code left in production bricks without promotion intent.\n5. Project-level orchestration that substitutes for a missing component.\n\n---\n\n## Examples\n\n<example>\n**Compliant**\n- A project composes `bases/api` with `components/user`, `components/auth`, `components/db`.\n- `bases/api` translates HTTP and delegates domain actions to component interfaces.\n- `components/user` exposes a small interface namespace; implementation stays private.\n- CI identifies affected projects since the last stable tag and tests those compositions.\n</example>\n\n<example type=\"invalid\">\n**Non-compliant**\n- Business logic added under `projects/customer-app/src`.\n- `components/order` directly requires `components/inventory.src.core`.\n- `bases/web` contains large amounts of reusable domain logic that belongs in a component.\n- Release workflow proceeds despite failed workspace validation.\n- Test workflow validates only isolated namespaces without checking affected project compositions.\n</example>\n\n---\n\n## Agent implications\n\n### Implementation agent\n- MAY create or modify code in bases and components.\n- MUST NOT introduce business logic into deployable projects.\n- MUST preserve interface boundaries across components.\n\n### Review agent\n- MUST inspect dependency edges across bricks.\n- MUST fail changes that bypass component interfaces.\n- SHOULD elevate review scope when interfaces change.\n\n### Test agent\n- MUST validate affected bricks in project context.\n- SHOULD distinguish brick-level from project-level test intent.\n- SHOULD prefer real component composition where practical.\n\n### Release agent\n- MUST require successful validation before release progression.\n- SHOULD derive release scope from changed-and-affected projects relative to a stable tag.\n- MUST NOT treat structurally invalid workspaces as releasable.",
               :id :std/polylith-composition,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "311",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (311): Enforce Polylith architectural integrity — bricks hold production logic, interfaces are contracts, validation gates workflows"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Treat Polylith as an architectural control tool — preflight reasoning, canonical workflow, role-specific operational requirements",
               :agent-behavior
               "The Polylith tool governs **legal structural changes** in a Polylith workspace.\nAgents MUST treat Polylith as a structural reasoning and validation tool, not\nmerely as a code generation context.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :audit,
                :message
                "Standard: Treat Polylith as an architectural control tool — preflight reasoning, canonical workflow, role-specific operational requirements"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:review :plan :implement},
                :file-globs
                ["components/**"
                 "bases/**"
                 "projects/**"
                 "development/**"
                 "workspace.edn"
                 "deps.edn"
                 ".github/workflows/**"]},
               :severity :minor,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Polylith Workspace Architecture Tool (MDC `mdc.tool.polylith`)\n\n## Purpose\n\nThe Polylith tool governs **legal structural changes** in a Polylith workspace.\nAgents MUST treat Polylith as a structural reasoning and validation tool, not\nmerely as a code generation context.\n\nIt is used to inspect workspace structure; identify bricks and projects;\ndetermine where new logic belongs; enforce interface-based composition;\nvalidate dependency legality; determine affected projects; support\nproject-context testing; and gate downstream review, release, and packaging\nworkflows.\n\nThis MDC is the **operational companion** to the normative rule at\n`frameworks/polylith-composition` (dewey 311). The rule defines what is\nnormatively true; this MDC defines how agents must behave to comply. If the\nMDC conflicts with the normative rule, the rule wins.\n\n---\n\n## When agents MUST invoke Polylith reasoning\n\nBefore any of the following, agents MUST use this MDC:\n\n- adding new production functionality\n- modifying component interfaces\n- introducing or changing cross-brick dependencies\n- creating a new component or base\n- deciding whether a change belongs in a base, component, project, or development\n- running workspace validation\n- determining test or release scope\n- explaining project impact of a change\n- reviewing PRs that modify workspace structure\n\n## When agents MUST NOT proceed without this reasoning\n\n<critical>\nAgents MUST NOT proceed to implementation when:\n- ownership of the change is unclear\n- a component interface might need to change\n- a new cross-brick dependency might be introduced\n- a deployable project appears to be gaining production code\n- the change may affect multiple projects\n- a release or test workflow depends on workspace validity\n</critical>\n\nIn any of these, perform the preflight reasoning below first.\n\n---\n\n## Inviolable invariants (summary)\n\nFull detail in `frameworks/polylith-composition` (dewey 311).\n\n1. Production logic belongs in bricks — not `projects/*/src`.\n2. Bases are boundary adapters — not homes for reusable domain logic.\n3. Components are consumed only through interfaces.\n4. Interface changes are contract changes.\n5. Structural validation is a hard gate before downstream workflows.\n6. Testing must reflect deployable project composition.\n7. Release scope must be change-derived against a stable reference point.\n\n---\n\n## Required preflight reasoning\n\nBefore implementing a non-trivial change, answer these questions. Include\nthe answers in planning metadata or review output when feasible.\n\n### Ownership\n- Which existing brick owns this responsibility?\n- If none does, is a new component or base warranted — or would that just be convenient?\n\n### Placement\n- Is this reusable production logic, boundary logic, project composition, or dev-only?\n- Should it live in a component, base, project, or `development/`?\n\n### Interface impact\n- Does this require a new interface function?\n- Is it purely internal to the component?\n- Will it alter a contract used by other bricks?\n\n### Dependency legality\n- Will this introduce a cross-brick dependency?\n- If so, does that dependency target an interface namespace?\n- Does this create an illegal architectural edge?\n\n### Project impact\n- Which deployable projects include the changed brick?\n- Which projects are affected transitively?\n- Which tests and workflows must run because of that impact?\n\n### Validation readiness\n- What structural checks must pass before the change is valid?\n- What evidence will demonstrate the workspace remains compliant?\n\n---\n\n## Canonical workflow\n\n1. **Inspect the workspace** — relevant components, bases, projects, interfaces, current dependency shape.\n2. **Determine ownership** — existing brick, new brick (with justification), `development/`, or project composition only.\n3. **Determine contract impact** — interface change, implementation-only change, composition change, or affected-project expansion.\n4. **Implement only in legal locations** — components for reusable behavior, bases for boundary concerns, `development/` for dev-only, projects for composition/configuration.\n5. **Validate structure** — run `poly check` (or equivalent) before progressing.\n6. **Validate behavior** — brick tests + affected-project tests + project-level runtime tests as appropriate.\n7. **Report impact** — changed bricks, interface changes, affected projects, validation status, test scope executed, residual risk.\n\n---\n\n## Operational requirements by agent role\n\n### Implementation agents\n- MUST determine owning brick before writing code.\n- MUST prefer modifying an existing brick over creating a new one without reason.\n- MUST preserve interface boundaries.\n- MUST NOT place production business logic in deployable projects.\n- MUST NOT import another component's implementation namespaces.\n- SHOULD minimize interface surface area.\n- SHOULD keep bases thin and delegating.\n\n### Review agents\n- MUST inspect new and changed cross-brick dependencies.\n- MUST fail changes that bypass component interfaces.\n- MUST flag production logic introduced under `projects/*/src`.\n- MUST elevate review scope when interfaces change.\n- SHOULD identify bases that have accumulated reusable domain logic.\n- SHOULD distinguish implementation-only changes from contract changes.\n\nReview output SHOULD state whether: interface boundaries were preserved,\nownership placement was correct, any illegal dependency edges exist, and\nproject impact scope is accurate.\n\n### Test agents\n- MUST validate changed bricks in the context of affected projects where material.\n- MUST distinguish brick-level tests from project-level tests.\n- SHOULD prefer real component composition over excessive mocking.\n- SHOULD mock only true external boundaries or impractical side effects.\n- MUST NOT claim completeness if only isolated namespace testing was performed when project composition is material.\n\nTest output SHOULD state: changed bricks tested, affected projects\nconsidered, whether project-context validation was performed, and known\ngaps between isolated and composed testing.\n\n### Release agents\n- MUST require successful structural validation before release progression.\n- SHOULD determine scope from changed-and-affected projects relative to a stable or release tag.\n- MUST NOT treat a structurally invalid workspace as releasable.\n- MUST NOT release arbitrary project subsets without impact reasoning.\n\nRelease output SHOULD state: comparison anchor used, changed projects,\naffected projects, tests/validation completed, and remaining release risk.\n\n---\n\n## Allowed and disallowed moves\n\n### Allowed\n- Add reusable domain logic to an existing component.\n- Add a new interface function to support intentional component collaboration.\n- Add boundary translation logic to a base.\n- Create a new component when responsibility does not fit an existing one.\n- Move exploratory code into `development/` first.\n- Derive release scope from affected-project analysis.\n- Widen review/test scope when an interface changes.\n\n### Disallowed\n- Add general production logic under `projects/*/src`.\n- Import another component's internal implementation namespace.\n- Use a base as a shared business-logic utility library.\n- Create a new brick without checking for an existing owner.\n- Bypass structural validation because local tests passed.\n- Assume isolated tests are sufficient when project composition is the delivery contract.\n- Release based only on touched files without affected-project reasoning.\n\n---\n\n## Tool-facing structured outputs\n\nWhen this MDC is used, agents SHOULD produce structured outputs that include\nas many of the following as are relevant. These are especially useful for\ncompilation into EDN policy or workflow evidence.\n\n- `owningBrick`\n- `changeKind` — one of `implementation` | `interface` | `base-boundary` | `project-composition` | `development-only`\n- `newDependencies`\n- `illegalDependencies`\n- `affectedProjects`\n- `requiresValidation`\n- `requiresProjectContextTesting`\n- `stableReference`\n- `releaseImpact`\n- `architecturalRiskNotes`\n\n---\n\n## Recommended prompt framing\n\nWhen an agent is about to make a change in a Polylith workspace, it SHOULD\ninternally frame the task as:\n\n> Determine the owning brick, determine whether the interface contract\n> changes, preserve legal dependency edges, validate workspace structure,\n> and verify affected project behavior.\n\nThat framing is architecturally correct. Do NOT frame as:\n\n> Add the requested code somewhere appropriate.\n\nThat framing erodes the model over time.\n\n---\n\n## Example decision patterns\n\n<example>\n**Adding new reusable business behavior**\n\nCorrect:\n- Identify owning component.\n- Extend component internals.\n- Add or modify interface only if needed.\n- Update affected callers through the interface.\n- Validate structure.\n- Test in affected project context.\n</example>\n\n<example type=\"invalid\">\n**Adding new reusable business behavior — anti-pattern**\n\n- Add a helper directly to a project namespace.\n- Import component internals from another brick.\n- Skip impact analysis because local tests passed.\n</example>\n\n<example>\n**Adding a new HTTP endpoint**\n\nCorrect:\n- Add route and translation logic in the relevant base.\n- Delegate domain behavior to a component interface.\n- Keep business rules in a component.\n- Test endpoint behavior in project context.\n</example>\n\n<example type=\"invalid\">\n**HTTP endpoint — anti-pattern**\n\n- Implement endpoint and business logic entirely in the base.\n- Duplicate domain behavior already present in another component.\n</example>\n\n<example>\n**Temporary integration logic during exploration**\n\nCorrect:\n- Place temporary orchestration or exploratory workflow code under `development/`.\n- Promote only intentional, production-worthy logic into a brick later.\n</example>\n\n<example type=\"invalid\">\n**Exploration — anti-pattern**\n\n- Leave exploratory code embedded in a production component or project indefinitely.\n</example>\n\n---\n\n## Detection signals (for policy compilation)\n\nCompilers or downstream policy systems MAY derive enforcement signals such as:\n\n- new namespace under `projects/*/src`\n- import of non-interface namespace from another brick\n- interface namespace modification (elevates review scope)\n- base namespace accumulating excessive domain behavior\n- missing workspace validation step before downstream workflow\n- missing affected-project analysis in release/test pipeline\n- mismatch between changed bricks and executed project-context tests\n\nThese signals support enforcement of the architecture rule but do not\nsubstitute for architectural reasoning.",
               :id :std/polylith-tool,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "312",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (312): Treat Polylith as an architectural control tool — preflight reasoning, canonical workflow, role-specific operational requirements"}
        #:rule{:title "PR documentation guidelines",
               :agent-behavior
               "1. **Automatically create** a PR doc file in `docs/pull-requests/`\n2. **Use the current date** (YYYY-MM-DD format)\n3. **Transform branch name** (replace `/` with `-`)",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message "Standard: PR documentation guidelines"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement}},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Pull Request Documentation Convention\n\n## Purpose\n\nMaintain structured, version-controlled documentation for all pull requests to provide context for:\n\n- Future developers and AI assistants\n- Historical reference and pattern analysis\n- Migration tracking and decision documentation\n- Architectural evolution understanding\n\n## Directory Structure\n\n```zsh\ndocs/\n└── pull-requests/\n    ├── 2026-01-04-migrate-protocols-to-composition-pattern.md\n    ├── 2026-01-15-feat-add-fsm-component.md\n    └── 2026-02-01-refactor-workflow-unit-tests.md\n```\n\n## Naming Convention\n\n**Format**: `YYYY-MM-DD-branch-name.md`\n\n**Components**:\n\n- `YYYY-MM-DD`: Date when PR was created (ISO 8601 date format)\n- `branch-name`: Git branch name (replace `/` with `-`)\n\n**Examples**:\n\n- Branch `feat/add-module` → `2026-01-18-feat-add-module.md`\n- Branch `fix/security-issue` → `2026-01-18-fix-security-issue.md`\n\n## File Location\n\n**Standard path**: `docs/pull-requests/YYYY-MM-DD-branch-name.md`\n\n**Why this location?**\n\n- Clear semantic meaning (`docs/` for documentation)\n- Easy to find and browse\n- Automatically included in repository searches\n- Available as context for AI assistants\n- Version controlled alongside code changes\n\n## When to Create\n\n**AUTOMATIC**: Create a PR doc immediately when creating a new feature branch.\n\n**Trigger conditions** (any of these):\n\n1. Creating a new branch with prefix: `feat/`, `fix/`, `refactor/`, `migrate/`, `chore/`\n2. Running `git checkout -b <branch-name>`\n3. User mentions creating a branch for new work\n\n**Skip for**:\n\n- Branches named `main`, `nonprod`\n- Trivial typo fixes (single commit, <5 lines changed)\n- Automated dependency updates (dependabot, renovate)\n\n## Required Content\n\n### Minimum Sections\n\n```markdown\n# [Conventional Commit Prefix]: [Title]\n\n## Overview\nBrief summary of what this PR does and why.\n\n## Motivation\nWhy is this change needed? What problem does it solve?\n\n## Changes in Detail\nList of specific changes, organized by category or component.\n\n## Testing Plan\nHow will this be validated? What tests were run?\n\n## Deployment Plan\nHow and when will this be deployed? Any special considerations?\n\n## Related Issues/PRs\nLinks to related work, issues, or dependencies.\n\n## Checklist\n- [ ] Task 1\n- [ ] Task 2\n```\n\n### Optional Sections (Use When Relevant)\n\n- **Architecture Changes**: Before/after diagrams or explanations\n- **Breaking Changes**: What breaks and migration path\n- **Rollback Plan**: How to undo if needed\n- **Performance Impact**: Expected performance changes\n- **Security Considerations**: Security implications\n- **Documentation Updates**: What docs were updated\n- **Dependencies**: Other PRs that must merge first\n\n## Lifecycle: Living Documents\n\n**PR docs are living documents** that evolve throughout the PR lifecycle:\n\n| Phase | Action |\n|----|-----|\n| **Creation** | Create doc when starting significant work |\n| **During Development** | Update as scope changes, decisions are made, or new learnings emerge |\n| **Before Merge** | Ensure doc reflects final state of the PR |\n| **After Merge** | Doc becomes static historical record |\n\n**Key principle**: The PR doc should always reflect the current understanding of the PR. If you add a feature,\n                   fix a bug discovered during review, or change approach, update the doc.\n\n## Agent Behavior\n\n**CRITICAL**: When you see or execute `git checkout -b <branch>` for a feature branch, **immediately create the PR doc**\n              before any other work. This is automatic, not optional.\n\nWhen creating a PR or preparing to open one:\n\n1. **Automatically create** a PR doc file in `docs/pull-requests/`\n2. **Use the current date** (YYYY-MM-DD format)\n3. **Transform branch name** (replace `/` with `-`)\n4. **Include comprehensive content**:\n   - Clear overview and motivation\n   - Detailed changes list\n   - Testing and deployment plans\n   - Checklists for validation\n5. **Reference in commits**: Mention the PR doc in the final commit message\n6. **Continuously update**: Keep the doc current as the PR evolves - it's a living document until merged\n\n### Example Workflow\n\n```bash\n# When user says: \"Let's create a PR for this migration\"\n1. Create: docs/pull-requests/2026-01-04-migrate-protocols-to-composition-pattern.md`\n2. Write comprehensive PR description in that file\n3. Commit the file along with the changes:\n   git add docs/pull-requests/2026-01-04-migrate-protocols-to-composition-pattern.md`\n4. Reference in commit message:\n   \"feat: migrate protocols (see docs/pull-requests/2026-01-04-migrate-protocols-to-composition-pattern.md')\"\n```\n\n## Repository Maintenance\n\n### Cleanup Policy\n\n**Keep all PR docs** - they serve as historical record.\n\nIf the repository grows too large (>100 PR docs):\n\n- Move old docs to `docs/pull-requests/archive/YYYY/` by year\n- Keep recent year in root `docs/pull-requests/`\n\n### .gitignore\n\n**Do NOT ignore** these files. They should be committed to git.\n\nEnsure `.gitignore` does NOT contain:\n\n```zsh\ndocs/pull-requests/\n*.md\n```\n\n## Benefits\n\n✅ **Context for AI**: LLMs can read historical PRs to understand patterns\n✅ **Knowledge Transfer**: New team members understand past decisions  \n✅ **Pattern Documentation**: Repeated patterns become obvious\n✅ **Migration Tracking**: Easy to see what's been migrated and how\n✅ **Decision Record**: Why decisions were made, not just what changed\n✅ **Searchable**: Can grep through PR docs for specific topics\n✅ **Template Source**: Previous PRs serve as templates for similar work\n\n## Anti-Patterns to Avoid\n\n❌ **Don't** create PR docs in the PR description only (GitHub UI) - put them in the repo\n❌ **Don't** use arbitrary names like `PR_DESCRIPTION.md` without context\n❌ **Don't** skip the date prefix - chronological sorting is important  \n❌ **Don't** delete PR docs after merge - they're historical record\n❌ **Don't** make PR docs excessively long - aim for clarity over completeness\n\n## Examples\n\n### Good PR Doc Names\n\n- `2026-01-04-migrate-protocols-to-composition-pattern.md`\n- `2026-01-15-feat-add-fsm-component.md`\n- `2026-02-01-refactor-workflow-unit-tests.md`\n\n### Bad PR Doc Names\n\n- `PR.md` (no context)\n- `description.md` (no date, no branch)\n- `my-changes.md` (not descriptive)\n- `temp-pr-notes.md` (implies temporary)\n\n## Cross-Repository Consistency\n\nThis convention applies to **all** repositories\n\nUse the **same structure and naming** across all repos for consistency.",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/pr-documentation,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "721",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (721): PR documentation guidelines"}
        #:rule{:title
               "PR Layering — decompose work into stratified, incremental pull requests",
               :agent-behavior
               "Once you understand all work needed, organize PRs as a stratified DAG. Each PR is small, incremental, and layers on top of more foundational work. Merge from the bottom up.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message
                "Standard: PR Layering — decompose work into stratified, incremental pull requests"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement}},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# PR Layering (ALWAYS)\nOnce you understand all work needed, organize PRs as a stratified DAG. Each PR is small, incremental, and layers on top of more foundational work. Merge from the bottom up.\n\n## Core principle\n**Build the foundation before the floors.** Just as code dependencies flow downward through strata, PR dependencies should flow upward—foundations merge first, then domain, then application, then adapters.\n\n## PR decomposition strategy\n\n### 1. Map the work to strata\nBefore writing code, categorize all changes by stratum:\n- **Foundations PR(s)**: Types, schemas, constants, pure utilities\n- **Domain PR(s)**: Business rules, policies, invariants (pure functions)\n- **Application PR(s)**: Use-cases, orchestration, port definitions\n- **Adapter PR(s)**: Controllers, CLI handlers, event listeners\n- **Infrastructure PR(s)**: DB implementations, external service clients\n\n### 2. Order PRs bottom-up\nCreate PRs in dependency order so each can merge independently:\n\n```\nPR 1: Foundations  ──┐\nPR 2: Domain       ──┼──► PR 4: Adapters\nPR 3: Application  ──┘         │\n                               ▼\n                        PR 5: Integration / wiring\n```\n\n### 3. Keep each PR atomic\n- **One stratum per PR** (preferred) or closely related strata\n- **< 400 lines** of meaningful change (tests don't count toward limit)\n- **Single reviewable concern**: a PR should answer one question—\"Does this type work?\", \"Is this business rule correct?\", \"Does this adapter translate properly?\"\n- **Independently mergeable**: each PR compiles, passes tests, and leaves main in a working state\n\n## PR description template\nWhen opening a layered PR, include:\n\n```markdown\n## Layer\n[Foundations | Domain | Application | Adapter | Infrastructure]\n\n## Depends on\n- #<PR-number> (title) — [merged | open]\n\n## What this adds\nBrief description of the incremental capability.\n\n## Strata affected\n- `namespace.or.module` — what changed and why\n```\n\n## Agent behavior (Cursor)\nWhen planning a feature or refactor:\n\n1. **Produce a PR plan first** — before writing code, output:\n   - The list of PRs by stratum\n   - The dependency DAG between PRs\n   - Estimated size (S/M/L) for each\n\n2. **Work bottom-up** — implement and propose changes for the lowest stratum first. Don't start on adapters until domain is solid.\n\n3. **Flag scope creep** — if a change in one stratum requires touching a higher stratum, split it out into a follow-up PR.\n\n4. **Suggest branch strategy** — for stacked PRs, recommend:\n   ```\n   main\n    └── feat/user-auth-types       (PR 1: Foundations)\n         └── feat/user-auth-domain (PR 2: Domain)\n              └── feat/user-auth-api (PR 3: Adapter)\n   ```\n\n## Anti-patterns to reject\n- **Monolith PRs**: 1000+ line PRs touching multiple strata—split them.\n- **Top-down PRs**: Starting with adapters, then \"backfilling\" domain—invert the order.\n- **Circular PR dependencies**: PR A needs PR B, and B needs A—refactor the design.\n- **Orphan PRs**: PRs that can't merge because a dependency is stuck—unblock or re-scope.\n- **Speculative foundations**: Adding types/utilities \"just in case\"—only add what the next stratum needs.\n\n## Benefits\n- **Faster reviews**: Reviewers focus on one layer at a time.\n- **Lower risk**: Small merges = small blast radius.\n- **Parallel work**: Multiple devs can work on different strata once interfaces are defined.\n- **Clear rollback**: If adapters break, domain and foundations remain intact.\n- **Documentation**: The PR chain itself documents the architecture.\n\n## Example: Adding user authentication\n\n| PR | Stratum | Contents | Depends on |\n|----|---------|----------|------------|\n| 1 | Foundations | `User`, `Credentials`, `AuthToken` types | — |\n| 2 | Domain | `validate-credentials`, `hash-password`, `verify-token` | PR 1 |\n| 3 | Application | `AuthService` port, `LoginUseCase`, `RefreshTokenUseCase` | PR 2 |\n| 4 | Infrastructure | `PostgresUserRepo`, `JWTTokenService` | PR 3 |\n| 5 | Adapter | `/login`, `/refresh` HTTP handlers | PR 3, PR 4 |\n\nEach PR is reviewable in isolation. Foundations can merge to main immediately; each subsequent layer merges once its dependencies land.",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/pr-layering,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "720",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (720): PR Layering — decompose work into stratified, incremental pull requests"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Pre-commit hook discipline and bypass constraints",
               :agent-behavior
               "**Pre-commit hooks enforce quality gates. Bypassing them violates miniforge's self-validation principle.**",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message
                "Standard: Pre-commit hook discipline and bypass constraints"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement}},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Pre-Commit Hook Discipline (ALWAYS)\n\n## Core Principle\n\n**Pre-commit hooks enforce quality gates. Bypassing them violates miniforge's self-validation principle.**\n\nThe pre-commit hook runs:\n- **Linting** (clj-kondo for Clojure)\n- **Formatting** (markdownlint for Markdown)\n- **Tests** (full test suite via `bb pre-commit`)\n- **Email validation** (must use @miniforge.ai)\n\nFailures indicate **real problems** that must be fixed, not bypassed.\n\n---\n\n## NEVER Bypass Without Investigation\n\n**CRITICAL**: When `bb pre-commit` or the git pre-commit hook fails, **NEVER** immediately use `git commit --no-verify`.\n\n### Required Investigation Steps (Before Bypass)\n\nWhen a pre-commit hook fails, you MUST:\n\n1. **Read the full error output** - Don't assume what's failing\n2. **Check what's staged** - Run `git diff --cached --stat` to see exactly what files are staged\n3. **Identify the root cause:**\n   - Are you staging unintended files? (e.g., `git add -A` in a dirty worktree)\n   - Are there legitimate test failures?\n   - Are there linting errors in your new code?\n   - Is there a pre-existing issue unrelated to your changes?\n4. **Fix the root cause:**\n   - If staging too many files: `git reset` and stage only your changes\n   - If test failures: Fix the tests or the code causing them\n   - If linting errors: Fix the code\n   - If pre-existing issues: Fix them in your PR (you're improving the codebase)\n\n### Bypass is Only Allowed When\n\nUse `git commit --no-verify` **ONLY** when **ALL** of these conditions are met:\n\n1. ✅ You've completed all investigation steps above\n2. ✅ You've documented the **specific reason** in the commit message with `[BYPASS-HOOKS: reason]`\n3. ✅ The failure is **environmental** (e.g., missing tools, permission issues) and **NOT** code quality\n4. ✅ Manual validation confirms:\n   - Tests pass: `clojure -M:poly test` (or equivalent)\n   - Linting passes: `bb lint:clj` for staged Clojure files\n   - Formatting passes: `bb fmt:md` for staged Markdown files\n5. ✅ You're committing to a feature branch (never bypass on main)\n6. ✅ CI will catch the issue if you're wrong\n\n### Bypass Commit Message Format\n\nWhen bypass is necessary, use this exact format:\n\n```bash\ngit commit --no-verify -m \"$(cat <<'EOF'\nfeat: your commit message here\n\n[BYPASS-HOOKS: reason]\nPre-commit hook failed due to: <specific environmental reason>\n\nManual validation:\n- Tests passed: clojure -M:poly test (exit code 0)\n- Linting passed: bb lint:clj (exit code 0)\n- Formatting passed: bb fmt:md (exit code 0)\n\nRoot cause: <what actually failed and why>\nWhy bypass: <why fixing it isn't possible right now>\nCI validation: Will be enforced by CI workflow\nEOF\n)\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Anti-Patterns to Reject\n\n❌ **\"Pre-commit is broken in this worktree\"** - Investigate why, don't bypass\n❌ **\"Tests pass manually but hook fails\"** - Investigate what the hook is doing differently\n❌ **\"It's taking too long\"** - Speed is not a valid reason\n❌ **\"CI will catch it anyway\"** - That's wasteful; fix it now\n❌ **\"It's a minor warning\"** - Fix minor warnings; they accumulate into major debt\n❌ **\"I'll fix it in the next commit\"** - Fix it in THIS commit\n❌ **\"The hook suggests I can bypass\"** - The hook also says \"BUT YOU REALLY SHOULDN'T!\"\n\n---\n\n## Agent Behavior (Cursor)\n\n### When Pre-Commit Fails\n\n1. **STOP** - Don't immediately try `--no-verify`\n2. **READ** the full error output (don't truncate)\n3. **CHECK** staging: `git diff --cached --stat`\n4. **IDENTIFY** the specific failure:\n   - What command failed? (lint/format/test)\n   - What files are affected?\n   - Is it your new code or pre-existing?\n5. **FIX** the root cause:\n   - If staging issue: Reset and stage correctly\n   - If test failure: Fix the test or code\n   - If linting: Fix the code\n   - If pre-existing: Fix it in your PR\n6. **VERIFY** the fix: Re-run the specific failing command\n7. **COMMIT** normally (no `--no-verify`)\n\n### When to Alert the User\n\nIf you discover:\n- Pre-existing test failures blocking your commit\n- Linting errors in files you didn't touch\n- Environmental issues preventing hook execution\n\nAlert the user with:\n1. **What's failing** (specific command and error)\n2. **Why it's failing** (root cause analysis)\n3. **Proposed fix** (correct solution, not bypass)\n4. **Impact** (blocks commit until resolved)\n\nAsk the user for guidance on how to proceed.\n\n### Red Flags in Your Reasoning\n\nIf you find yourself thinking:\n- \"The hook might have environmental issues\"\n- \"Tests passed manually, so it's probably fine\"\n- \"We can bypass this once\"\n- \"CI will catch it\"\n\n**STOP.** You're about to make a poor decision. Go back to investigation steps.\n\n---\n\n## Pre-Commit Hook Failures are Learning Opportunities\n\nWhen the hook fails, it's teaching you:\n- You're staging too many files\n- Your code has quality issues\n- There are pre-existing problems to fix\n- Your git workflow needs refinement\n\n**Embrace the failure, investigate, and fix.** Don't bypass your way around learning.\n\n---\n\n## Exception: True Emergencies\n\nIn a true emergency (production down, security incident), document extensively:\n\n```bash\ngit commit --no-verify -m \"$(cat <<'EOF'\nhotfix: emergency fix for production outage\n\n[BYPASS-HOOKS: EMERGENCY]\nProduction is down. Incident: INC-12345\nImpact: 100% of users affected\nTime sensitivity: Every minute costs $$$\n\nThis commit:\n- Rolls back problematic deployment\n- Restores service immediately\n- Will be followed by proper fix with tests in PR #XXX\n\nPre-commit bypassed to restore service ASAP.\nPost-incident review will happen in INC-12345.\nEOF\n)\"\n```\n\nEmergencies are **RARE**. Feature development is never an emergency.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n| Situation | Action | Tool |\n|-----------|--------|------|\n| Pre-commit fails | Investigate root cause | Read errors, check staging |\n| Staging issue | Fix staging | `git reset`, stage correctly |\n| Test failure | Fix test/code | Debug, fix, re-test |\n| Linting error | Fix code | Address linter feedback |\n| Environmental issue | Document & bypass OR fix environment | `--no-verify` with extensive docs |\n| Emergency | Document extensively & bypass | `--no-verify` with incident details |\n| **Default** | **Fix the issue** | **Never bypass** |\n\n**When in doubt: Don't bypass. Investigate and fix.**",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/pre-commit-discipline,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "715",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (715): Pre-commit hook discipline and bypass constraints"}
