        #:rule{:title
               "Result handling — use success?/failed? predicates and success/anomaly constructors",
               :agent-behavior
               "1. Use `schema/success` or `schema/failure` — never `{:success? true ...}`.\n2. When checking a result from a called function, use `schema/succeeded?` or `schema/failed?` — never `:success?` key access.\n3. If the result type comes from a different component, check what predicates that component's interface exports. If none exist, that's a gap to flag.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message
                "Standard: Result handling — use success?/failed? predicates and success/anomaly constructors"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement}},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Result Handling (ALWAYS)\n\nOperations that can fail return a **result map**. Always use the provided predicates and constructors — never build result maps by hand or reach into their structure directly.\n\n## Predicates over structure inspection\n\n**Never** examine the shape of a result to determine success or failure. Use the predicates.\n\n```clojure\n;; BAD — reaching into the result map's internals\n(if (:success? result)\n  ...)\n\n(when (= :ok (:status result))\n  ...)\n\n(when (nil? (:error result))\n  ...)\n\n;; GOOD — use predicates\n(if (schema/succeeded? result)\n  ...)\n\n(when (schema/succeeded? result)\n  ...)\n```\n\nThe internal shape of a result map is an **implementation detail**. Code that depends on `:success?` being a boolean key breaks when the result format evolves. Predicates are the stable API.\n\n## Constructors over hand-built maps\n\n**Never** construct result maps with `{:success? true ...}` or `{:status :error ...}` literals. Use the provided constructors.\n\n```clojure\n;; BAD — hand-building result maps\n{:success? true  :data value  :errors nil}\n{:success? false :error \"Something went wrong\"}\n{:success? false :errors [{:msg \"invalid\"}]}\n\n;; GOOD — use schema constructors\n(schema/success :data value {:errors nil})\n(schema/failure :data error-message)\n(schema/failure-with-errors :data [{:msg \"invalid\"}])\n```\n\nConstructors enforce the canonical shape. They are also self-documenting: `(schema/failure-with-errors :pack errors)` communicates intent; `{:success? false :pack nil :errors errors}` does not.\n\n## Propagation — thread results through, don't unwrap\n\nWhen passing a result to a caller, propagate the result map — don't unwrap it and re-wrap it.\n\n```clojure\n;; BAD — unwrapping and re-wrapping\n(let [{:keys [success? data error]} (load-pack path)]\n  (if success?\n    {:ok true :pack data}\n    {:ok false :msg error}))\n\n;; GOOD — propagate\n(let [result (load-pack path)]\n  (if (schema/succeeded? result)\n    (process (:pack result))\n    result))  ; return the failure as-is for the caller\n```\n\n## What counts as an \"anomaly\"\n\nUse anomaly constructors (failure forms) for:\n- Validation failures (invalid input at a boundary)\n- Missing required resources (file not found, entity not found)\n- Downstream errors caught at a boundary\n\nDo NOT wrap expected nil return values as anomalies. A function that legitimately returns nil for \"not found\" is not failing — it's answering the question.\n\n## Agent behavior\n\nWhen writing code that returns a result:\n1. Use `schema/success` or `schema/failure` — never `{:success? true ...}`.\n2. When checking a result from a called function, use `schema/succeeded?` or `schema/failed?` — never `:success?` key access.\n3. If the result type comes from a different component, check what predicates that component's interface exports. If none exist, that's a gap to flag.\n4. When propagating failures up the call stack, return the result map unchanged — don't add new keys or translate the error.\n\n## Anti-patterns to reject\n\n- `(when (:success? result) ...)` — use predicate\n- `(assoc result :success? false)` — use constructor\n- `(if (nil? (:error result)) ...)` — use predicate\n- `(not (:failed? result))` — use `(succeeded? result)`\n- Mixing result-map checks with exception handling in the same function — separate concerns",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/result-handling,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "003",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (003): Result handling — use success?/failed? predicates and success/anomaly constructors"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Use ALWAYS when asked to CREATE A RULE or UPDATE A RULE or taught a lesson from the user that should be retained as a new rule for Cursor",
               :agent-behavior
               "```mdc\n---\ndewey: \"NNN\"\ndescription: ACTION when TRIGGER to OUTCOME\nglobs: *.mdc\n---",
               :enforcement
               {:action :audit,
                :message
                "Standard: Use ALWAYS when asked to CREATE A RULE or UPDATE A RULE or taught a lesson from the user that should be retained as a new rule for Cursor"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{}, :file-globs [".cursor/rules/**/*.mdc"]},
               :severity :minor,
               :knowledge-content
               "# LLM Rules Format\n\n## Core Structure\n\n```mdc\n---\ndewey: \"NNN\"\ndescription: ACTION when TRIGGER to OUTCOME\nglobs: *.mdc\n---\n\n# Rule Title\n\n## Context\n- When to apply this rule\n- Prerequisites or conditions\n\n## Requirements\n- Concise, actionable items\n- Each requirement must be testable\n\n## Examples\n<example>\nGood concise example with explanation\n</example>\n\n<example type=\"invalid\">\nInvalid concise example with explanation\n</example>\n```\n\n## File Organization\n\n### Location\n\n- Root: `.cursor/rules/`\n- Extension: `.mdc`\n- Structure: `<category-slug>/<rule-slug>.mdc`\n- Dewey code: in frontmatter (`dewey: \"NNN\"`), not in the filename or path\n\n```zsh\n.cursor/rules/\n├── index.mdc           # Master catalog (dewey: \"000\")\n├── foundations/        # dewey 000-099\n├── languages/          # dewey 200-299\n├── frameworks/         # dewey 300-399\n├── workflows/          # dewey 700-799\n├── project/            # dewey 800-899\n└── meta/               # dewey 900-999\n```\n\n### Dewey Ranges\n\n```\n000-099  Foundations & Core Principles\n100-199  Development Environment & Tools\n200-299  Languages\n300-399  Frameworks & Platforms\n400-499  Testing & Quality\n500-599  Operations & Infrastructure\n600-699  Documentation\n700-799  Workflows & Processes\n800-899  Project-Specific\n900-999  Meta & Templates\n```\n\nPrivate rules: `_name.mdc` (underscore prefix)\n\n### Glob Pattern Examples\n\nCommon glob patterns for different rule types:\n\n- Core standards: .cursor/rules/*.mdc\n- Language rules: src/**/*.{js,ts}\n- Testing standards: **/*.test.{js,ts}\n- React components: src/components/**/*.tsx\n- Documentation: docs/**/*.md\n- Configuration files: *.config.{js,json}\n- Build artifacts: dist/**/*\n- Multiple extensions: src/**/*.{js,jsx,ts,tsx}\n- Multiple files: dist/**/*, docs/**/*.md\n\n## Required Fields\n\n### Frontmatter\n\n- description: ACTION TRIGGER OUTCOME format\n- globs: `glob pattern for files and folders`\n\n### Body\n\n- <version>X.Y.Z</version>\n- context: Usage conditions\n- requirements: Actionable items\n- examples: Both valid and invalid\n\n## Formatting Guidelines\n\n- Use Concise Markdown primarily\n- XML tags limited to:\n  - <example>\n  - <danger>\n  - <required>\n  - <rules>\n  - <rule>\n  - <critical>\n  - <version>\n- Always indent content within XML or nested XML tags by 2 spaces\n- Keep rules as short as possbile\n- Use Mermaid syntax if it will be shorter or clearer than describing a complex rule\n- Use Emojis where appropriate to convey meaning that will improve rule understanding by the AI Agent\n- Keep examples as short as possible to clearly convey the positive or negative example\n\n## AI Optimization Tips\n\n1. Use precise, deterministic ACTION TRIGGER OUTCOME format in descriptions\n2. Provide concise positive and negative example of rule application in practice\n3. Optimize for AI context window efficiency\n4. Remove any non-essential or redundant information\n5. Use standard glob patterns without quotes (e.g., *.js, src/**/*.ts)\n\n## AI Context Efficiency\n\n1. Keep frontmatter description under 120 characters (or less) while maintaining clear intent for rule selection by AI AGent\n2. Limit examples to essential patterns only\n3. Use hierarchical structure for quick parsing\n4. Remove redundant information across sections\n5. Maintain high information density with minimal tokens\n6. Focus on machine-actionable instructions over human explanations\n\n<critical>\n  - NEVER include verbose explanations or redundant context that increases AI token overhead\n  - Keep file as short and to the point as possible BUT NEVER at the expense of sacrificing \n    rule impact and usefulness for the AI Agent.\n  - the front matter can ONLY have the fields description and globs.\n</critical>",
               :id :std/rule-format,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "900",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (900): Use ALWAYS when asked to CREATE A RULE or UPDATE A RULE or taught a lesson from the user that should be retained as a new rule for Cursor"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Reject bind mounts of host container-runtime sockets into the capsule",
               :agent-behavior
               "Bind-mounting `/var/run/docker.sock` (or an equivalent runtime socket)\ninto a capsule grants the container full control over the host's\ncontainer daemon. A task that escapes its capsule via the socket can\nlaunch arbitrary containers, read every other capsule's filesystem, and\nignore every other isolation control miniforge applies.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message
                "Standard: Reject bind mounts of host container-runtime sockets into the capsule"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement}},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Runtime: no host docker socket (HARD-STOP)\n\nBind-mounting `/var/run/docker.sock` (or an equivalent runtime socket)\ninto a capsule grants the container full control over the host's\ncontainer daemon. A task that escapes its capsule via the socket can\nlaunch arbitrary containers, read every other capsule's filesystem, and\nignore every other isolation control miniforge applies.\n\nThis is the single most catastrophic capsule-isolation failure mode.\nReject it on sight.\n\n## Detection\n\nReject any execution-plan `:mounts` entry whose `:host-path` matches:\n\n- `/var/run/docker.sock`\n- `/run/docker.sock`\n- `/var/run/podman/podman.sock`\n- `/run/podman/podman.sock`\n- `/var/run/containerd/containerd.sock`\n- `/run/containerd/containerd.sock`\n- Any path ending in `docker.sock`, `podman.sock`, or `containerd.sock`\n\nThe check is host-path-based; bind-mount target inside the capsule does\nnot matter. A user who renames the mount target to `/etc/passwd` is\nstill mounting the host socket.\n\n## Enforcement\n\n- **Action:** `:hard-stop`\n- **Phases:** `:plan`, `:implement`, `:verify`, `:release`\n- **Scope:** every execution plan; no opt-out, no exceptions\n\n## Why no opt-out\n\nIf a workflow legitimately needs to control the host's runtime, the\nruntime adapter is the wrong layer for that. Add a host-side capability\nexplicitly (e.g. an `:executor :host-runtime-broker` with its own\nauthentication and audit trail). Mounting the socket bypasses every\naudit point miniforge has.\n\n## Spec reference\n\n- N11-delta §6 `:runtime/no-host-docker-socket`\n- N11 §2.2 (capsule filesystem boundary)\n- N6 (evidence & provenance — host-socket access has no provenance story)",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/runtime-no-host-docker-socket,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "030",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (030): Reject bind mounts of host container-runtime sockets into the capsule"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Reject execution plans whose :image-digest is anything other than a sha256:<64-hex> content digest",
               :agent-behavior
               "Container image tags are mutable. `task-runner-clojure:latest` on\nMonday is not the same image as Tuesday. A workflow that runs against\na tag has no reproducibility story — re-running the same execution\nplan produces different artifacts; evidence bundles point at content\nthat might no longer exist.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message
                "Standard: Reject execution plans whose :image-digest is anything other than a sha256:<64-hex> content digest"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement}},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Runtime: require image digest pin\n\nContainer image tags are mutable. `task-runner-clojure:latest` on\nMonday is not the same image as Tuesday. A workflow that runs against\na tag has no reproducibility story — re-running the same execution\nplan produces different artifacts; evidence bundles point at content\nthat might no longer exist.\n\nPer N6 (Evidence & Provenance) and N11-delta §5, execution plans MUST\ncarry a content-addressed image digest in the plan's `:image-digest`\nfield. The schema (`ExecutionPlanSchema` in\n`components/dag-executor/.../execution_plan.clj`) types `:image-digest`\nas `:string`; the **value** convention — enforced by this rule — is\n`sha256:<64 hex chars>`.\n\nThis rule fires on the digest field, not on image references in\ngeneral. Image references with their registry/repo path (e.g.\n`docker.io/miniforge/task-runner-clojure@sha256:...`) are passed\nseparately to the runtime CLI as the image to pull/run. The\n`:image-digest` field is the bare digest captured for evidence and\nreproducibility.\n\n## Detection\n\nInspect the execution plan's `:image-digest`. The acceptable value is\nexactly a `sha256:` digest with 64 hex chars:\n\n- `:pass` — `sha256:<64 hex chars>`\n- `:violation` — anything else (tag, full image reference, blank, malformed)\n\n```clojure\n(let [d (:image-digest plan)]\n  (if (and (string? d)\n           (re-matches #\"^sha256:[a-f0-9]{64}$\" d))\n    :pass\n    :violation))\n```\n\n## Enforcement\n\n- **Action:** `:hard-stop`\n- **Phases:** `:plan`, `:release`\n- **Scope:** every execution plan; no opt-out\n\n## Why no opt-out\n\nReproducibility and the evidence-bundle audit trail are non-negotiable\nfor governed execution. A workflow that legitimately needs the latest\nbuild of an image should resolve the tag to a digest at plan-build\ntime and write the digest into `:image-digest`; running with anything\nother than a digest defeats the audit story.\n\n## Interaction with `runtime/images.edn`\n\nThe default image references in `runtime/images.edn`\n(e.g. `docker.io/miniforge/task-runner-clojure:latest`) are image\nreferences, not `:image-digest` values. This rule does NOT fire on\nthem. It fires on the `:image-digest` that the plan-build phase writes\ninto the execution plan after resolving the reference; the\nplan-builder is responsible for performing that resolution before the\nexecutor sees the plan.\n\n## Spec reference\n\n- N11-delta §5 (image references must be fully qualified)\n- N11-delta §6 `:runtime/require-image-digest-pin`\n- N6 (evidence & provenance — digest pinning is the audit primitive)",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/runtime-require-image-digest-pin,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "033",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (033): Reject execution plans whose :image-digest is anything other than a sha256:<64-hex> content digest"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Prefer rootless container runtimes; warn or hard-stop when the resolved runtime advertises no :rootless capability",
               :agent-behavior
               "A rootless container runtime maps the in-container UID/GID to a user\nnamespace on the host, so a container break-out lands the attacker on\nthe host as the unprivileged miniforge user rather than as root. Podman\nis rootless by default; Docker requires opt-in setup.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message
                "Standard: Prefer rootless container runtimes; warn or hard-stop when the resolved runtime advertises no :rootless capability"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement}},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Runtime: require rootless\n\nA rootless container runtime maps the in-container UID/GID to a user\nnamespace on the host, so a container break-out lands the attacker on\nthe host as the unprivileged miniforge user rather than as root. Podman\nis rootless by default; Docker requires opt-in setup.\n\nMiniforge does not refuse to run under a rooted runtime — that would\nbreak Docker users on day one. It does declare the difference visible\nin the descriptor's capability set, and policy-aware deployments can\ntreat the absence of `:rootless` as a hard-stop.\n\n## Detection\n\nRead the runtime descriptor's `:runtime/capabilities` set. The check\nis data-only — no probing required.\n\n```clojure\n(if (descriptor/capable? descriptor :rootless)\n  :pass\n  :violation)\n```\n\n## Enforcement\n\n- **OSS default:** `:warn`\n- **Governed Fleet workflows:** `:hard-stop` (configurable via policy\n  pack)\n- **Phases:** `:plan`, `:release`\n\n## Why split warn / hard-stop\n\nThe OSS posture is \"Podman is recommended; Docker works\". A hard-stop\non Docker would defeat that. The fleet posture is stricter — fleet\nworkflows process external PRs and the rootless requirement is a real\ndefense-in-depth gain. Policy packs differentiate.\n\n## Spec reference\n\n- N11-delta §6 `:runtime/require-rootless`\n- N11-delta §4 (capability set)",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/runtime-require-rootless,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "031",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (031): Prefer rootless container runtimes; warn or hard-stop when the resolved runtime advertises no :rootless capability"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Restrict bind mounts of host paths to an explicit allowlist; flag everything outside for review",
               :agent-behavior
               "Every bind mount from the host into a capsule expands the capsule's\nblast radius. Mounting `<repo>/ exposes the whole filesystem. Even mounts\nintended as read-only often turn out to be writable in practice via\ninode-level operations the runtime doesn't catch.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message
                "Standard: Restrict bind mounts of host paths to an explicit allowlist; flag everything outside for review"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement}},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Runtime: restrict host mounts\n\nEvery bind mount from the host into a capsule expands the capsule's\nblast radius. Mounting `<repo>/ exposes the whole filesystem. Even mounts\nintended as read-only often turn out to be writable in practice via\ninode-level operations the runtime doesn't catch.\n\nDefault to requiring human review for host mounts that aren't on a\nsmall allowlist; let the user opt in deliberately for the cases that\nneed it.\n\n## Allowlist\n\nA bind mount is allowed without review when its `:host-path` is one\nof:\n\n- The miniforge workspace directory (resolved at execution-plan build\n  time)\n- The miniforge secret-material mount points (resolved similarly)\n- The shared model cache directory (`~/.miniforge/model-cache` or the\n  configured equivalent)\n\nAnything else falls into review.\n\n## Detection\n\nFor each `:mounts` entry, check `:host-path` against the allowlist.\nMounts whose host path is outside the allowlist trigger this rule.\n\n```clojure\n(when (and (:host-path mount)\n           (not (allowlisted-host-path? (:host-path mount))))\n  :review)\n```\n\n## Enforcement\n\n- **Action:** `:review` (do not auto-block; surface to a human in the\n  control plane decision card)\n- **Phases:** `:plan`, `:release`\n\n## Why review, not hard-stop\n\nSome workflows legitimately mount custom paths — a build cache, a\nshared dataset, a fixture directory. Hard-stopping every non-allowlist\nmount would force every such workflow into the allowlist-extension\nprocess, which is high-friction. Review surfaces the decision to a\nhuman; the allowlist captures the patterns that recur.\n\n## Spec reference\n\n- N11-delta §6 `:runtime/restrict-host-mounts`\n- N11 §2.2 (capsule filesystem boundary)",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/runtime-restrict-host-mounts,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "032",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (032): Restrict bind mounts of host paths to an explicit allowlist; flag everything outside for review"}
        #:rule{:title "Rust style and idioms",
               :agent-behavior
               "See also: `foundations/stratified-design` and `foundations/simple-made-easy` — those rules apply in Rust\nwithout exception. This file covers Rust-specific idioms that sit on top of those foundations.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :audit,
                :message "Standard: Rust style and idioms"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:review :implement},
                :file-globs ["**/*.rs" "**/Cargo.toml"]},
               :severity :minor,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Rust style guide\n\nSee also: `foundations/stratified-design` and `foundations/simple-made-easy` — those rules apply in Rust\nwithout exception. This file covers Rust-specific idioms that sit on top of those foundations.\n\n## Crate and module structure\n\n- Use Cargo workspaces with small crates and explicit boundaries.\n- Keep domain logic in crates that have no dependency on transport or framework crates (Axum, tonic,\n  etc.). Adapters live in their own crates.\n- Keep FFI surfaces narrow, stable, and JSON-schema aligned.\n- Prefer `struct`/`enum` data modeling over trait-heavy abstractions. Reach for traits when you need\n  open polymorphism; do not create trait hierarchies as a substitute for thinking about data shapes.\n- One major type per module is a useful default; group supporting types nearby, not scattered.\n\n### Thin orchestration index modules\n\nWhen a module is the public face of a bounded area with multiple sub-surfaces, the index file\n(`<name>.rs` or `mod.rs`) routes, delegates, and re-exports. It does not also own helpers.\nSub-surfaces live in named submodules; the split is by bounded concern, not by file size.\n\n```rust\n// Good — index file routes by mode, submodules own concerns\nmod chrome;\nmod detail;\nmod monitor;\n\npub fn render(app: &App, frame: &mut Frame) {\n    match app.mode {\n        Mode::Monitor => monitor::render(app, frame),\n        Mode::Detail  => detail::render(app, frame),\n    }\n}\n\n// Bad — index file accretes helpers across surfaces\npub fn render(app: &App, frame: &mut Frame) { /* 300 lines mixing modes */ }\nfn fmt_workflow_row(...) { ... }\nfn fmt_agent_row(...) { ... }\nfn correlate_pr_state(...) { ... }\n// ...\n```\n\nReasons:\n\n- Index files document the surface set. New reviewers find the entry points without scrolling.\n- Visibility and `pub use` discipline is a design choice, not an afterthought.\n- Submodules can be moved or split without rewriting orchestration.\n\nThe underlying \"no god modules\" principle is in `foundations/stratified-design` and\n`foundations/code-quality`. The Rust-specific addendum is the index-file shape and the\n`pub use` discipline.\n\nDo not create `utils.rs` or `helpers.rs` dumping grounds. The first extraction target is a\nnamed bounded concern (`encoding`, `correlation`, `formatting`), not an unnamed bucket. If\nyou cannot name what binds the helpers together, they do not yet belong in a shared module.\n\n## Naming\n\nFollow standard Rust conventions:\n\n| Item | Convention | Example |\n|------|-----------|---------|\n| Types (struct, enum, trait) | `UpperCamelCase` | `CautionContext` |\n| Functions and methods | `snake_case` | `evaluate_regime` |\n| Local variables | `snake_case` | `family_buckets` |\n| Modules | `snake_case` | `rule_engine` |\n| Constants and statics | `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE` | `MAX_RETRIES` |\n| Type parameters | Short `UpperCamelCase` | `T`, `Err` |\n\nUse long, descriptive names for locals — code completion makes short names a false economy. Default\nvariable names to use consistently:\n\n- `res` — result being built\n- `ctx` — context bundle\n- `acc` — accumulator\n- `it` — iteration variable when the name does not matter\n\nAvoid ad-hoc abbreviations. Use the established set (`db`, `ctx`, `acc`) or spell it out.\n\nNames that clash with keywords: mangle rather than use raw identifiers (`r#`):\n\n```\ncrate  → krate\nenum   → enum_\nfn     → func\nimpl   → imp\nmod    → module\nstruct → strukt\ntrait  → trait_\ntype   → ty\n```\n\n## Data-driven policy patterns\n\nCentralize business rules as data, not scattered conditionals — the Rust application of\nsimple-made-easy's \"rules live in one place\" principle.\n\n### Context structs\n\nBundle related evaluation inputs into a named struct. Functions that share the same inputs should\nshare the same context type.\n\n```rust\n// Good: context bundles related state\nstruct CautionContext<'a> {\n    style_id: &'a str,\n    regime: &'a str,\n    family_buckets: BTreeMap<&'a str, Option<&'a str>>,\n}\n\n// Bad: six loose parameters threaded through call chains\nfn evaluate(regime: &str, conc: bool, families: &[F], confidence: &str, ...) -> R\n```\n\n### Rule tables over conditional chains\n\nReplace `if`/`match` chains that encode policy with `const` rule tables. Each entry is a\npredicate + payload. This applies equally to large `match` expressions — when the arms are\nencoding policy, pull them into a table.\n\n```rust\n// Good: policy as data\nstruct CautionRule {\n    predicate: fn(&CautionContext) -> bool,\n    message: &'static str,\n}\n\nconst CAUTION_RULES: &[CautionRule] = &[\n    CautionRule { predicate: |ctx| ctx.family_is_red(\"valuation\"), message: CAUTION_VALUATION },\n    CautionRule { predicate: |ctx| ctx.regime == \"defensive\",     message: CAUTION_EDUCATIONAL },\n];\n\nfn cautions(ctx: &CautionContext) -> Vec<String> {\n    CAUTION_RULES.iter().filter(|r| (r.predicate)(ctx)).map(|r| r.message.to_string()).collect()\n}\n\n// Bad: scattered if-chains\nif family_is_red(\"valuation\") { cautions.push(...) }\nif family_is_red(\"yield_curve\") { cautions.push(...) }\nif regime == \"defensive\" { cautions.push(...) }\n```\n\n### Resolution structs\n\nWhen a function selects from alternatives, return a named struct — not a tuple.\n\n```rust\n// Good\nstruct PlaybookResolution { regime: String, thesis: String, targets: BTreeMap<String, f64> }\n\n// Bad: positional tuple leaking internal ordering\nlet (regime, thesis, targets, id, rationale) = resolve(...);\n```\n\n### String constants\n\nAll user-facing and advisory text lives in a `strings.rs` module as `pub const`. Domain logic\nreferences `crate::strings::*` — never inline string literals in business logic.\n\n## Error handling\n\n### Library crates: use `thiserror`\n\nDefine typed error enums for each crate. `thiserror` derives `std::error::Error`, `Display`, and\n`From` with minimal boilerplate:\n\n```rust\n#[derive(Debug, thiserror::Error)]\npub enum ServiceError {\n    #[error(\"Database error: {0}\")]\n    Db(#[from] DbError),\n    #[error(\"Invalid data: {0}\")]\n    InvalidData(String),\n    #[error(transparent)]\n    Serialization(#[from] serde_json::Error),\n}\n```\n\nFor layered systems, nest error enums with `#[from]` to preserve context at each boundary.\n\n### Binary crates: `anyhow` is acceptable\n\n`anyhow::Result` is appropriate in `main`, CLI entry points, and test helpers where ergonomic\npropagation matters more than precise error types. Do not use `anyhow` in library crates — it\nerases type context that callers need.\n\nUse `anyhow::format_err!` rather than `anyhow::anyhow` (less stuttering).\n\n### General error rules\n\n- Prefer `Result`; avoid `panic!` except for genuine programmer errors (`unreachable!`, `todo!`,\n  test assertions).\n- Do not use `.unwrap()` or `.expect()` in production code paths. Prefer `let Ok(x) = ... else`\n  for early returns, `?` for bubbling, or combinator methods (`unwrap_or`, `unwrap_or_else`).\n- Use `?` to propagate errors rather than verbose `match` chains.\n- Async errors that cross `.await` boundaries must implement `Send + Sync + 'static`.\n- Separate parse failures, transport failures, and stale-cache behavior explicitly — do not collapse\n  them into a single opaque error variant.\n- Test error paths: check `err.to_string()` when `PartialEq` is not available.\n\n## Type idioms\n\n### Prefer general borrowed types on function boundaries\n\nUse the more general borrowed form:\n\n| Prefer | Over |\n|--------|------|\n| `&str` | `&String` |\n| `&[T]` | `&Vec<T>` |\n| `Option<&T>` | `&Option<T>` |\n| `&Path` | `&PathBuf` |\n\n### `Copy` types\n\nDerive `Copy` for small plain-data structs (up to ~3 words / 24 bytes) whose fields are all `Copy`.\nDo not derive `Copy` on types containing `String`, `Vec`, or other heap-owning fields.\n\n### Constructors\n\nPrefer `#[derive(Default)]` over a zero-argument `new()` when the zero value is correct. Avoid\ninventing \"dummy\" default states just to satisfy `Default`.\n\n### Getters\n\nIf a field has an invariant, make it `private`, enforce it in the constructor, and expose a getter\nthat returns a borrowed form:\n\n```rust\n// Good\nfn first_name(&self) -> &str { self.first_name.as_str() }\nfn middle_name(&self) -> Option<&str> { self.middle_name.as_ref() }\n\n// Bad — clones unnecessarily, or leaks container type\nfn first_name(&self) -> String { self.first_name.clone() }\nfn middle_name(&self) -> &Option<String> { &self.middle_name }\n```\n\nNever provide setters. If mutation is needed after construction, provide a builder or use\n`pub` fields when there are no invariants to protect.\n\n## Boundary commands and pipeline selection\n\nRules that govern how requests cross a boundary into a Rust crate, and how phases or modes\nselect among pure pipelines. Both rules sit on top of the data-driven policy patterns above\n— they are the boundary-layer applications of the same principle.\n\n### Typed boundary commands\n\nA boundary that accepts more than one operation MUST express the operation set as an enum\nin `contracts`. The dispatch site MUST be an exhaustive `match` over that enum with no `_`\narm. JSON or other wire formats are decoded into the typed enum at the boundary, once.\n\n```rust\n// Good — typed boundary, exhaustive match\n#[derive(Debug, Clone, Deserialize)]\n#[serde(tag = \"command\", content = \"params\", rename_all = \"snake_case\")]\npub enum Command {\n    Ping,\n    ListPortfolios(ListPortfoliosParams),\n    EvaluateAlerts(EvaluateAlertsParams),\n}\n\npub fn route(ctx: &Ctx, cmd: Command) -> Response {\n    match cmd {\n        Command::Ping => ping(ctx),\n        Command::ListPortfolios(p) => portfolio::list(ctx, p),\n        Command::EvaluateAlerts(p) => alerts::evaluate(ctx, p),\n    }\n}\n\n// Bad — stringly-typed dispatch with non-exhaustive match\nmatch envelope.command.as_str() {\n    \"ping\"             => ping(ctx),\n    \"list_portfolios\"  => portfolio::list(ctx, &envelope.params),\n    other              => Response::error(format!(\"unknown: {other}\")),\n}\n```\n\nReasons:\n\n- Adding a command becomes a compile error in every dispatch site until handled.\n- Parameter decoding is centralized in `Deserialize` impls, not scattered across\n  `params.get(\"...\").and_then(|v| v.as_str())` chains in handlers.\n- The wire-format string set is single-sourced from the `#[serde(rename_all)]` derive.\n\nWhen the operation list is itself dynamic (plugins, packs, pluggable adapters), prefer a\ntyped envelope wrapping a registry lookup over an open string match.\n\n### Pipeline selection by enum\n\nWhen a phase, mode, tier, or policy determines which sequence of pure functions runs,\nencode the selector as an enum and define one pipeline function per variant. Stages\nthemselves do not branch on the selector — the *pipeline function* picks the stage variant.\n\n```rust\n// Good — pipeline selection lives in one place\npub enum Phase { IngestOnly, Score, Full }\n\npub fn run(phase: Phase, ctx: &Ctx, input: Raw) -> Result<Out, PipelineError> {\n    match phase {\n        Phase::IngestOnly => ingest_only(ctx, input).map(Out::Ingest),\n        Phase::Score      => score(ctx, input).map(Out::Scored),\n        Phase::Full       => full(ctx, input).map(Out::Signal),\n    }\n}\n\nfn full(ctx: &Ctx, input: Raw) -> Result<Signal, PipelineError> {\n    let a = ingest::run(ctx, input)?;\n    let b = extract::run(ctx, a)?;\n    let c = canonicalize::run(ctx, b)?;\n    score::run(ctx, c).and_then(|s| signal::run(ctx, s))\n}\n\n// Bad — phase branching scattered through stages\nfn extract(ctx: &Ctx, x: A) -> Result<B, PipelineError> {\n    if ctx.phase == Phase::IngestOnly { return Ok(B::skipped()); }\n    if ctx.policy == InferencePolicy::LocalOnly { ... } else { ... }\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nReasons:\n\n- Adding a phase = one new variant + one new function + one new arm. No grep across stages.\n- Stages stay pure and composable: their type signature is `(&Ctx, In) -> Result<Out, _>`,\n  not `(&Ctx, In, Phase, Tier, Policy) -> Result<Out, _>`.\n- Test surface is tractable — each pipeline function is a tested unit; stages are tested\n  independently of phase composition.\n\n### Bounded data-driven content\n\nWhen a static table holds *operational content* that is tuned by domain owners (numeric\nthresholds, weights, metric definitions, layout/composition metadata, selectors), it lives\nin a RON or TOML file under `<crate>/resources/`, loaded once and cached. When a table\nholds *structural* identifiers referenced from code (cluster IDs, source-type tags,\nschema-version strings), it stays as `pub const &'static str` in a Rust module.\n\nUser-facing or advisory copy is **out of scope** for this rule and stays in `strings.rs`\n(see \"String constants\" earlier). Content files reference stable keys or enum variants\ninto `strings.rs` rather than embedding display text directly.\n\nHeuristic: if a non-engineer would reasonably want to edit the value without changes to\nhandlers, it is content; move it. If editing it requires changes to handlers that key on\nit, it is structure; keep it as `const`.\n\nThe two viable load mechanisms — pick deliberately:\n\n- `include_str!` — embeds the file at compile time. The owning crate rebuilds when the\n  file changes; consumers do not re-source against new code. Use when the binary must be\n  self-contained (desktop apps, signed bundles).\n- Filesystem read at startup — file ships alongside the binary and is read at process\n  start. Edits do not require a rebuild of the owning crate. Use when ops can swap the\n  resource file without redeploying the binary.\n\nEither mechanism MUST validate at startup and fail loudly on malformed input via a typed\nerror, not via `panic`/`expect`. Lazy initialization via `OnceLock::get_or_init` is\nacceptable, but eager validation at process start is preferred so format errors surface\nbefore the first request.\n\n```rust\n// Good — typed error, eager startup validation, no expect/panic\n#[derive(Debug, thiserror::Error)]\npub enum RegistryLoadError {\n    #[error(\"registry: malformed TOML: {0}\")]\n    Parse(#[from] toml::de::Error),\n}\n\n#[derive(Debug, Deserialize)]\nstruct RegistryFile { metric: Vec<SourceEntry> }\n\npub fn load_registry() -> Result<&'static [SourceEntry], RegistryLoadError> {\n    static REGISTRY: OnceLock<Vec<SourceEntry>> = OnceLock::new();\n    if let Some(loaded) = REGISTRY.get() {\n        return Ok(loaded.as_slice());\n    }\n    let raw = include_str!(\"../resources/registry.toml\");\n    let parsed: RegistryFile = toml::from_str(raw)?;\n    Ok(REGISTRY.get_or_init(|| parsed.metric).as_slice())\n}\n\n// Process startup calls load_registry() once and bails on error before serving traffic.\n\n// Bad — 36 hand-typed `SourceEntry { ... }` literals inside a fn\npub fn default_registry() -> Vec<SourceEntry> {\n    vec![\n        SourceEntry { id: \"shiller_pe\", warn_threshold: 30.0, alert_threshold: 35.0, ... },\n        SourceEntry { id: \"vix\", warn_threshold: 20.0, alert_threshold: 30.0, ... },\n        // 34 more\n    ]\n}\n\n// Bad — panics on malformed input, violates the \"no expect in production\" rule\npub fn registry() -> &'static [SourceEntry] {\n    static REGISTRY: OnceLock<Vec<SourceEntry>> = OnceLock::new();\n    REGISTRY.get_or_init(|| {\n        let raw = include_str!(\"../resources/registry.toml\");\n        toml::from_str::<RegistryFile>(raw).expect(\"malformed\").metric  // ← do not\n    })\n}\n```\n\nReasons:\n\n- Tunable content edits are localized to the resource file. No handler / API surface\n  changes ripple into consuming crates.\n- Domain owners can review/diff a TOML file without reading Rust.\n- Format errors fail at startup with a typed error, not at the first call site and not\n  via panic.\n- Pick of `include_str!` vs filesystem read is an explicit deployment decision rather\n  than an implicit one.\n\nConstraints:\n\n- Content files MUST be loaded once and cached. Do not re-read on every call.\n- Content files MUST be validated against the deserialized type. A malformed file is a\n  startup error returned via `Result`, not an `unwrap()`/`expect()` panic.\n- Content files MUST be checked into the repo alongside their consumer. They are not\n  configuration; they are data.\n- The load mechanism (compile-time embed vs runtime read) MUST be a deliberate choice,\n  documented at the loader.\n\n### Derived context at boundary seams\n\nWhen a boundary needs correlated data from several entity families and more than one\nsibling consumer would otherwise repeat the same join, build one immutable derived context\nonce at the seam and pass it downward.\n\nTrigger (both must hold):\n\n- response or surface shape spans **two or more entity families**, AND\n- **two or more sibling consumers** would otherwise repeat the same correlation logic.\n\nBelow the trigger, this pattern is overkill — a three-field response does not need a\nparameter object.\n\n```rust\n// Good — one builder owns the correlation; renderers take the derived view\npub struct RunDossier {\n    pub anchor: WorkflowRun,\n    pub workflows: Vec<WorkflowRun>,\n    pub agents: Vec<AgentSession>,\n    pub pending_decisions: Vec<DecisionCard>,\n}\n\npub fn build_run_dossier(anchor: &WorkflowRun, state: &SupervisoryState) -> RunDossier {\n    // collect once, sort once, correlate once\n}\n\npub fn render_summary(dossier: &RunDossier, theme: &Theme) -> Vec<Line<'static>> { /* ... */ }\npub fn render_agents(dossier: &RunDossier, theme: &Theme)  -> Vec<Line<'static>> { /* ... */ }\n\n// Bad — sibling renderers each rescan root state, each invent fallback joins\npub fn render_summary(state: &SupervisoryState, run_id: Uuid, theme: &Theme) -> Vec<Line<'static>> {\n    let workflows = state.workflows.values().filter(|w| w.correlation_id == run_id).collect();\n    let agents    = state.agents.values().filter(|a| /* same join, slightly different */).collect();\n    /* ... */\n}\npub fn render_agents(state: &SupervisoryState, run_id: Uuid, theme: &Theme)  -> Vec<Line<'static>> {\n    let agents    = state.agents.values().filter(|a| /* same join, drifted */).collect();\n    /* ... */\n}\n```\n\nConstraints:\n\n- The builder is a pure function over the authoritative state plus a small anchor input.\n- Join policy lives in the builder. Sibling consumers do not invent fallback correlation rules.\n- Downstream consumers take the context object, not root state.\n- Context types stay boundary-local. They do not become domain state, contract DTOs, or\n  cross-crate types — those have stricter compatibility rules and a derived view is the\n  wrong shape for either.\n\nReasons:\n\n- Single source of truth for the join produces consistent results across siblings; drift\n  between renderers (one filters by `correlation_id`, another by `workflow_key`) becomes\n  impossible.\n- Builder is the natural test seam: a few fixture states, a few expected dossiers, done.\n- Adding a section to the surface adds a field to the context, not a fourth full state scan.\n\nWatch for the god-context anti-shape: if the context grows fields used by exactly one\nunrelated consumer, or starts replacing domain/state boundaries, split it.\n\n## `impl Trait` vs generics vs `dyn Trait`\n\n- Prefer `impl Trait` in function arguments when the caller's concrete type is unimportant and you\n  want zero-cost static dispatch without spelling out a type parameter.\n- Use explicit `<T: Trait>` when you need to name `T` elsewhere in the signature (return type,\n  multiple parameters of the same type).\n- Reserve `dyn Trait` for cases where you genuinely need runtime polymorphism: heterogeneous\n  collections, plugin boundaries, or abstracting internals behind a stable interface. Avoid boxing\n  too early inside structs.\n- Prefer `&dyn Trait` over `Box<dyn Trait>` when ownership is not required.\n- Avoid `AsRef` polymorphism in non-library code — it inflates compile times without meaningful\n  benefit at call sites.\n\n## Functions and control flow\n\n### Preconditions in types\n\nExpress preconditions in types; do not check in the callee what the caller should have provided:\n\n```rust\n// Good — caller must supply a Walrus\nfn frobnicate(walrus: Walrus) { ... }\n\n// Bad — callee silently no-ops on None\nfn frobnicate(walrus: Option<Walrus>) {\n    let Some(walrus) = walrus else { return };\n    ...\n}\n```\n\n### Early returns\n\nUse early returns to reduce cognitive nesting. Use `return Err(...)` explicitly rather than `Err(...)?`:\n\n```rust\n// Good\nfn foo() -> Option<Bar> {\n    if !condition() {\n        return None;\n    }\n    Some(...)\n}\n```\n\n### Functions with many parameters\n\nReplace boolean flags and long parameter lists with a `Config` struct:\n\n```rust\n// Good\npub struct AnnotationConfig {\n    pub binary_target: bool,\n    pub annotate_runnables: bool,\n    pub annotate_impls: bool,\n}\n\npub fn annotations(db: &RootDatabase, file_id: FileId, config: AnnotationConfig) -> Vec<Annotation>\n\n// Bad\npub fn annotations(db: &RootDatabase, file_id: FileId, binary_target: bool,\n                   annotate_runnables: bool, annotate_impls: bool) -> Vec<Annotation>\n```\n\nDo not implement `Default` for `Config` structs; require callers to be explicit about every field.\n\n### Avoid \"doer\" objects\n\nPrefer a plain function over a struct constructed solely to call one method:\n\n```rust\n// Good\ndo_thing(arg1, arg2);\n\n// Bad\nThingDoer::new(arg1, arg2).do();\n```\n\nWhen an operation has genuine internal state, hide the struct behind a public function:\n\n```rust\npub fn do_thing(arg1: Arg1, arg2: Arg2) -> Res {\n    Ctx { arg1, arg2 }.run()\n}\n```\n\n### Helper variables\n\nIntroduce named variables for complex conditions rather than inline expressions. Single-use\nvariables are cognitively cheap and aid debugging.\n\n## Linting\n\n- Keep `cargo clippy --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings` clean.\n- Fix warnings; do not silence them with `#[allow(...)]` unless you understand the lint and document\n  why suppression is correct. Prefer `#[expect(...)]` with a comment — it re-warns if the lint\n  becomes inapplicable.\n- Do not add `#[allow(dead_code)]` to suppress incomplete work; remove the dead code or add a\n  tracked issue.\n- Configure lint levels in `Cargo.toml` `[workspace.lints]` rather than per-file attributes.\n\n## Memory and allocation\n\n- Borrow (`&T`) rather than clone (`T::clone()`) by default. Clone deliberately when you need\n  an owned copy.\n- Do not clone inside iterator chains — use `.cloned()` or `.copied()` at the chain boundary.\n- Avoid collecting into a `Vec` when an iterator suffices.\n- For recursive collection-building functions, use an accumulator parameter instead of returning\n  and merging fresh collections on each recursion.\n- Avoid monomorphizing large functions across crate boundaries — use a thin generic wrapper that\n  delegates to a `&dyn Fn` implementation.\n\n## Import style\n\nGroup imports separated by blank lines in this order: `std`, external crates, `crate::`, `super::`\n/ `self::`. Re-exports should be rare and placed after imports. Avoid local `use MyEnum::*`.\n\n## Documentation\n\n- Write `///` doc comments on all public items (functions, structs, traits, enums, constants).\n- Include a `# Errors` section when a function returns `Result`, a `# Panics` section when it can\n  panic, and a `# Safety` section when it contains `unsafe`.\n- Write runnable `# Examples` in doc comments — they become `cargo test` test cases.\n- Use `//!` module/crate-level comments at the top of `lib.rs` or `mod.rs`.\n- Inline `//` comments explain *why*, not *what*. Start comments with a capital letter and end with\n  a period. Named comment kinds (`// SAFETY:`, `// CONTEXT:`, `// INVARIANT:`) signal intent.\n- Do not leave `// TODO` without a tracked issue reference.\n\n## Testing\n\nThe factory-function principle and \"tests are production code\" rule live in\n`testing/standards` (Dewey 400). This section covers the Rust mechanics on top of those.\n\n- Prefer fixture-based parity tests for contract compatibility (golden files, snapshot testing).\n- Add focused unit tests for pure domain functions: reducers, evaluators, regime logic.\n- Keep synthetic tests small and deterministic. Use `cargo insta` for snapshot tests.\n- Tests must exercise error paths, not just happy paths.\n- Do not use `#[should_panic]`; check `Err`/`None` explicitly.\n- Do not `#[ignore]` tests; assert the wrong behavior with a `// FIXME` if it is not yet correct.\n- Test snippets should be minimal — remove boilerplate not relevant to what is being tested.\n\n### `test_support` modules\n\nWhen a second test module in a crate starts hand-building the same entity shape, extract\na `test_support` module that owns canonical valid fixtures.\n\n```rust\n// crate/src/test_support.rs (or pub(crate) mod test_support; in lib.rs under #[cfg(test)])\npub(crate) fn workflow_run(id: Uuid) -> WorkflowRun { /* valid defaults */ }\npub(crate) fn pr_fleet_entry(repo: &str, number: u64) -> PrFleetEntry { /* valid defaults */ }\n```\n\nMechanics:\n\n- `pub(crate)` visibility is the default; cross-crate fixture sharing is rare and the\n  default is **not** to expose factories beyond the crate.\n- Factories produce valid defaults. Tests override only the fields relevant to the scenario,\n  using struct-update syntax: `WorkflowRun { status: WorkflowRunStatus::Failed, ..test_support::workflow_run(id) }`.\n- Shared status / priority / glyph vocabularies live in helpers, not duplicated `match`\n  ladders across test modules.\n- `test_support` is production-quality code: named constants, no copy-pasted constructors,\n  no giant anonymous maps. The same standards apply.\n- Place `test_support.rs` at the crate root for crate-wide reuse. Use `#[cfg(test)] mod\n  test_support;` if the fixtures must not be reachable from non-test builds.\n- Cross-crate test fixtures only become a separate `<crate>-test-support` workspace member\n  once duplication has persisted across two or more crates long enough to justify it.\n\n## What NOT to do\n\n- Do not scatter policy conditionals across modules. See rule tables above.\n- Do not use `unwrap`/`expect` in production call paths.\n- Do not use `anyhow` in library crates.\n- Do not add `#[allow(dead_code)]` to paper over incomplete work.\n- Do not create trait hierarchies as a substitute for reasoning about data shapes.\n- Do not clone prematurely inside loops or iterator chains.\n- Do not use `Box<dyn Trait>` inside structs unless runtime polymorphism is genuinely required.\n- Do not mix domain logic with transport concerns in the same crate (see stratified-design).\n- Do not dispatch boundary commands by `match s.as_str()`. Use a typed `Command` enum in\n  `contracts` with an exhaustive match.\n- Do not branch on phase / mode / tier / policy inside individual stage functions. Encode\n  the selector as an enum and select the pipeline once at the top.\n- Do not adopt an ECS (legion, bevy_ecs, hecs, specs) for service code. Service entity\n  counts and capability shapes do not justify it. Reserve ECS for genuine real-time\n  simulation; if it appears, prefer Bevy.\n- Do not encode \"capability by component presence\". Use Rust typestate (`PhantomData<Tag>`\n  or distinct types) when behavior depends on lifecycle state.\n- Do not add a crate-wide `prelude` module that pub-uses everything. Explicit imports are\n  the convention; rust-analyzer auto-import handles the ergonomic case.\n- Do not create `utils.rs` / `helpers.rs` / `common.rs` dumping grounds. The first\n  extraction target is a named bounded concern (`encoding`, `correlation`, `formatting`).\n- Do not let an index module (`mod.rs` / `<name>.rs`) own helpers across surfaces. Index\n  modules route, delegate, and re-export.\n- Do not promote a derived context object (e.g. `RunDossier`) into domain state, contract\n  DTOs, or cross-crate types. Derived contexts stay boundary-local.\n- Do not hand-build the same entity shape across test modules. Extract a `test_support`\n  factory the second time you reach for it.",
               :id :std/rust,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "230",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (230): Rust style and idioms"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Simple Made Easy — choose constructs with simpler artifacts, not easier authoring",
               :agent-behavior
               "- When proposing a design, include:\n- When editing code that’s overly complex:\n  - Suggest a “data first” rewrite of the hot path.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message
                "Standard: Simple Made Easy — choose constructs with simpler artifacts, not easier authoring"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement}},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Simple Made Easy (ALWAYS)\n\nOptimize for **simple artifacts** (unbraided, decoupled), not for what is **easy** (familiar, at hand).\nUsers live with the artifact, not the authoring experience.\n\n> “Simplicity is a prerequisite for reliability.” — Dijkstra  \n> Simple = one braid (uncomplected). Easy = familiar/near. Choose simple.\n\n## Decision rubric\n\nWhen choosing designs/constructs, prefer the option that **reduces intertwining** of concerns—even if it’s less familiar.\n\n- **Values over state**: prefer immutable values and pure functions; make state explicit, local, and small.\n- **Data over syntax**: represent information as plain data (maps, vectors, sets). Avoid DSL-ish micro-syntaxes unless necessary.\n- **Functions over methods**: favor small, stateless functions and namespaces over deep OO hierarchies.\n- **A-la-carte polymorphism**: choose open, decoupled dispatch (protocols/typeclasses/interfaces) over\n                               inheritance and giant enums/switches.\n- **Declarative over imperative**: use set/relational operations, queries, and rules for “what,” not “how.”\n- **Queues over calls (when/where)**: decouple time/place with message queues or async boundaries; don’t make A know B unnecessarily.\n- **Rules live in one place (why)**: centralize policy in data/rules tables or a rules engine, not scattered conditionals.\n\n## What / Who / How / When / Where / Why — keep separate\n\n- **What**: operations (names and contracts); small specs (inputs/outputs) live with the function/module.\n- **Who**: concrete implementers/adapters wired via DI; no leaking details across boundaries.\n- **How**: implementations chosen behind interfaces/ports; keep replaceable.\n- **When/Where**: scheduling, retries, concurrency, and topology belong at edges (adapter/config).\n- **Why**: policies and rules centralized; treat as data.\n\n## State & concurrency\n\n- Treat state as hazardous material:\n  - Justify it, minimize scope, isolate at the edge.\n  - Model with managed references/STM/actors only when true concurrency requires it.\n- Prefer idempotent, deterministic operations; make time and randomness injectable.\n\n## Change & debugging\n\n- Smaller surface area ⇒ fewer joints to break. Strive for modules you can reason about locally.\n- Reasonability beats tooling: if understanding requires a global tour, simplify the design.\n- Tests are nets, not wings: don’t rely on them to compensate for tangled designs.\n\n## PR checklist (Author & Reviewer)\n\n- **Simplicity**: Does this reduce entanglement vs alternatives? What did we *remove*?\n- **Boundaries**: Are What/Who/How/When/Where/Why separated?\n- **Data**: Is information represented as plain data, not hidden in code constructs?\n- **State**: Is state minimized, localized, and explicit? Why must it exist?\n- **Policy**: Are rules centralized and declarative?\n- **Swapability**: Can we replace implementations without touching callers?\n- **Evidence**: Include a short note comparing the “easy but complex” option you rejected.\n\n## Agent behavior\n\n- When proposing a design, include:\n  1) A short “simple vs easy” comparison (2–3 bullets).  \n  2) The minimal set of pure functions and data structures.  \n  3) Where any state/concurrency is confined and why it’s necessary.  \n  4) A rules/policy section expressed as data (table/map) if applicable.\n- When editing code that’s overly complex:\n  - Suggest a “data first” rewrite of the hot path.\n  - Extract policy into a dedicated rules module or data file.\n  - Replace switch/if jungles with open polymorphism where beneficial.\n\n## Red flags to push back on\n\n- Deep inheritance trees; giant God objects/services.\n- Conditionals scattered across the codebase encoding policy ad hoc.\n- ORM-driven domain models leaking persistence concerns everywhere.\n- Actor systems chosen “by default” where simple queues/calls suffice.\n- Tight coupling to frameworks in core logic (non-replaceable code).\n\n## Accept that simple ≠ fewer things\n\nIt’s okay if we end up with *more but smaller* modules. We’re minimizing braiding, not counting files.",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/simple-made-easy,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "010",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (010): Simple Made Easy — choose constructs with simpler artifacts, not easier authoring"}
